# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: term-limits-in-the-united-states
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Presidential elections were held in the United States from October 31 to December 3, 1800.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1800-united-states-presidential-election] This was the first presidential election in U.S. history to be a rematch, the first election where an incumbent president lost re-election, leading to the first time in modern history where a national government changed hands peaceably following a free election.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Adams had narrowly defeated Jefferson in the 1796 election.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Under the rules of the electoral system in place before the 1804 ratification of the Twelfth Amendment to the United States Constitution, each member of the Electoral College cast two votes, with no distinction made between electoral votes for president and electoral votes for vice president.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1800-united-states-presidential-election] As Jefferson received the second-most votes in 1796, he was elected vice president.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1800-united-states-presidential-election] In 1800, unlike in 1796, both parties formally nominated tickets.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1800-united-states-presidential-election] The Democratic-Republicans nominated a ticket consisting of Jefferson and Aaron Burr, while the Federalists nominated a ticket consisting of Adams and Charles Cotesworth Pinckney.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Each party formed a plan by which one of their respective electors would vote for a third candidate or abstain so that its preferred presidential candidate (Adams for the Federalists and Jefferson for the Democratic-Republicans) would win one more vote than the party's other nominee.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1800-united-states-presidential-election] The chief political issues revolved around the fallout from the French Revolution and the Quasi-War.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1800-united-states-presidential-election] The Federalists favored a strong central government and close relations with Great Britain.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1800-united-states-presidential-election] The Democratic-Republicans favored decentralization to the state governments, and the party attacked the taxes the Federalists imposed.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1800-united-states-presidential-election] The Democratic-Republicans also denounced the Alien and Sedition Acts, which the Federalists had passed to make it harder for immigrants to become citizens and to restrict statements critical of the federal government.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1800-united-states-presidential-election] The Democratic-Republicans were well organized at the state and local levels, while the Federalists were disorganized and suffered a bitter split between their two major leaders, Adams and Alexander Hamilton.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1800-united-states-presidential-election] According to historian John Ferling, the jockeying for electoral votes, regional divisions, and the propaganda smear campaigns created by both parties made the election recognizably modern.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1800-united-states-presidential-election] At the end of a long and bitter campaign, Jefferson and Burr each won 73 electoral votes, Adams won 65, and Pinckney won 64.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1800-united-states-presidential-election] The Federalists swept New England, the Democratic-Republicans dominated the South, and the parties split the Mid-Atlantic states of New York, New Jersey, and Pennsylvania.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1800-united-states-presidential-election] The Democratic-Republicans' assumption that one or more electors in Rhode Island, Vermont, New Jersey, Georgia, Kentucky, or Tennessee would vote for Jefferson and not Burr resulted in a tie, known as the Burr dilemma.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1800-united-states-presidential-election] It necessitated a contingent election in the House of Representatives.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Under the terms laid out in the Constitution, the outgoing House of Representatives chose between Jefferson and Burr.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Burr was accused of campaigning for the presidency himself in the contingent election despite being a member of Jefferson's party.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Each state delegation cast one vote, and a victory in the contingent election required one candidate to win a majority of the state delegations.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Neither Burr nor Jefferson was able to win on the first 35 ballots of the contingent election, as most Federalist representatives backed Burr and all Democratic-Republican representatives backed Jefferson.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Hamilton favored Jefferson over Burr, and he convinced several Federalists to switch their support to Jefferson, giving Jefferson a victory on the 36th ballot.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Jefferson became the second consecutive incumbent vice president to be elected president.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1800-united-states-presidential-election] This is one of two presidential elections (along with the 1824 election) that have been decided in the House.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Both parties used congressional nominating caucuses to formally nominate tickets for the first time.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1800-united-states-presidential-election] The Federalists nominated a ticket consisting of incumbent President John Adams of Massachusetts and Charles Cotesworth Pinckney of South Carolina.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Pinckney had fought in the American Revolutionary War and later served as the minister to France.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1800-united-states-presidential-election] The Democratic-Republicans nominated a ticket consisting of Vice President Thomas Jefferson of Virginia and former Senator Aaron Burr of New York.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Jefferson had been the runner-up in the previous election and had co-founded the party with James Madison and others, while Burr was popular in the electorally important state of New York.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1800-united-states-presidential-election] While the 1800 election was a re-match of the 1796 election, it ushered in a new type of American politics, a two-party republic and acrimonious campaigning behind the scenes and through the press.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1800-united-states-presidential-election] On top of this, the election pitted the "larger than life" Adams and Jefferson, who were formerly close allies turned political enemies.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1800-united-states-presidential-election] The campaign was bitter and characterized by slander and personal attacks on both sides.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Federalists spread rumors that the Democratic-Republicans were radical atheists who would ruin the country (based on the Democratic-Republican support for the French Revolution).
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1800-united-states-presidential-election] In 1798, George Washington had complained "that you could as soon scrub the blackamoor white, as to change the principles of a professed Democrat; and that he will leave nothing unattempted to overturn the Government of this Country".
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Meanwhile, the Democratic-Republicans accused Federalists of subverting republican principles with the Alien and Sedition Acts.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1800-united-states-presidential-election] They also accused Federalists of favoring Britain in its war with France in order to promote aristocratic, anti-democratic values.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Ideology played a central role with a Jeffersonian "left" supporting the French Revolution, versus a Federalist "right" opposing it.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Adams was attacked by both the opposition Democratic-Republicans and a group of so-called "High Federalists" aligned with Alexander Hamilton.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1800-united-states-presidential-election] "High Federalists" considered Adams too moderate and would have preferred the leadership of Alexander Hamilton instead.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Hamilton had apparently grown impatient with Adams and wanted a new president who was more receptive to his goals.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1800-united-states-presidential-election] During Washington's presidency, Hamilton had been able to influence the federal response to the Whiskey Rebellion (which threatened the government's power to tax citizens).
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1800-united-states-presidential-election] When Washington announced that he would not seek a third term, the Federalists and Adams regarded himself as next-in-line.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Hamilton appears to have hoped in 1796 that his influence within an Adams administration would be as great as or greater than in Washington's.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1800-united-states-presidential-election] By 1800, Hamilton had come to realize that Adams was too independent and thought the Federalist vice presidential candidate, Charles Cotesworth Pinckney of South Carolina, more suited to serving Hamilton's interests.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1800-united-states-presidential-election] In his third sabotage attempt toward Adams, Hamilton quietly schemed to elect Pinckney to the presidency.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Given Pinckney's lack of political experience, he would have been expected to be open to Hamilton's influence.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1800-united-states-presidential-election] However, Hamilton's plan backfired and hurt the Federalist party, particularly after one of his letters, a scathing criticism of Adams that was fifty-four pages long, fell into the hands of a Democratic-Republican and soon after became public.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1800-united-states-presidential-election] It embarrassed Adams and damaged Hamilton's efforts on behalf of Pinckney, not to mention speeding Hamilton's own political decline.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1800-united-states-presidential-election] The contemporarily unorthodox public campaigning methods employed in 1800 were first employed by Jefferson's running mate and campaign manager, Aaron Burr, who is credited by some historians with inventing the modern electioneering process.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Yet, throughout this entire process, the candidates themselves were conspicuously missing from the campaigning, at least publicly, due to fears that they may otherwise be tagged as "demagogues".
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Even a visit John Adams made to Washington was made into a public point of contention.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Partisans on both sides sought any advantage they could find.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1800-united-states-presidential-election] In several states, this included changing the process of selecting electors to ensure the desired result.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1800-united-states-presidential-election] In Georgia, Democratic-Republican legislators replaced the popular vote with selection by the state legislature.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1800-united-states-presidential-election] In Virginia, the Democratic-Republican-controlled legislature switched from electoral districts to a general ticket, a winner-take-all system.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Federalist legislators also switched methods, switching from districts and general tickets to legislature votes in Massachusetts and New Hampshire, respectively.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1800-united-states-presidential-election] In Pennsylvania, the General Assembly was split, with the Democratic-Republican-dominated House wishing to retain the general ticket and the Federalist-controlled Senate wishing to return to the district system, hoping to win at least some electoral votes.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Eventually, this deadlock was broken by a last-minute compromise between the chambers that gave the Democratic-Republican eight electors and the Federalists seven.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1800-united-states-presidential-election] In New York, the rejection to change the selection method backfired on the Federalists.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1800-united-states-presidential-election] In March 1800, two months before the assembly elections, the Democratic-Republicans attempted to pass a bill that would switch from a legislature vote to electoral districts, hoping they would secure at least a third of the state's seats.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1800-united-states-presidential-election] The Federalists defeated the measure, believing that they would win control of both chambers and award all of the state's electoral votes to the Federalist nominees.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1800-united-states-presidential-election] However, in the April state elections, Aaron Burr's effective mobilization of the vote in New York City led to a reversal of the Federalist majority in the state legislature, providing crucial support for the Democratic-Republican ticket.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1800-united-states-presidential-election] In response to the Federalist defeat, Hamilton attempted to get Governor John Jay to call a special session of the outgoing Federalist-dominated New York legislature.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Hamilton's plan was for the outgoing assembly to pass legislation that would establish the popular election of electors through electoral districts, a strategy almost certain to secure nine or ten of the twelve elector slots for the Federalists.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Jay refused to participate in such an underhanded scheme.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1800-united-states-presidential-election] The Federalist legislature in Connecticut did not change the method of voting but instead passed a "stand up" election law, mandating that all votes be cast publicly and orally, an intimidating procedure that ordinarily favored those in power.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1800-united-states-presidential-election] As election day neared, the election was too close to call.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1800-united-states-presidential-election] The last state to vote, South Carolina, chose its electors on December 2, and would become key to determining the election.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1800-united-states-presidential-election] The state elections in mid-October had produced an assembly that was about evenly divided between committed Federalists and Republicans, with 16 unaffiliated representatives who were all strongly pro-Jefferson.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Many of the elected Jeffersonians were also supporters of Pinckney, the revered native son of the state.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1800-united-states-presidential-election] If South Carolina's electors gave their votes to Jefferson and Pinckney, then Pinckney would place an electoral vote behind Jefferson, becoming the vice president.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1800-united-states-presidential-election] However, Pinckney stayed loyal to the instructions of his party's caucus and was adamant that any elector who voted for him must also vote for Adams.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1800-united-states-presidential-election] With uncommitted legislators not willing to desert Jefferson and Pinckney unwilling to abandon Adams, the uncommitted legislators eventually reluctantly agreed to support Burr.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Under the United States Constitution as it then stood, each elector cast two votes, and the candidate with a majority of the votes was elected president, with the vice presidency going to the runner-up.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1800-united-states-presidential-election] The Federalists therefore arranged for one of their Rhode Island electors to vote for John Jay instead of Charles Pinckney to prevent the election from resulting in a tie.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1800-united-states-presidential-election] A letter to Jefferson from Peter Freneau assured him that a member of the Republican delegation from South Carolina would vote for George Clinton instead of Aaron Burr and a report from Georgia indicated that two of its electors would deny Burr their votes.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1800-united-states-presidential-election] However, this information proved faulty.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Thus, all of the Democratic-Republican electors cast their votes for both Jefferson and Burr, 73 in all for each of them.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1800-united-states-presidential-election] According to a provision of the United States Constitution, a tie in a case of this type had to be resolved by the House of Representatives, with each state casting one vote.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1800-united-states-presidential-election] In the outgoing House, the Federalists had a majority of 60 seats to 46.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1800-united-states-presidential-election] When the electoral ballots were opened and counted on February 11, 1801, the certificate of election from Georgia was different than the others.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Georgia had sent the original oral ballot.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1800-united-states-presidential-election] In 2004, David Fontana and Bruce Ackerman asserted that Georgia's certificate did not take the constitutionally mandated form of a "List of all the Persons voted for, and of the Number of Votes for each".
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1800-united-states-presidential-election] They claimed that Vice President Jefferson, who was presiding over the counting of electoral votes in his role as President of the Senate, immediately counted the votes from Georgia as votes for Jefferson and Burr, though they observed that "no objections were raised".
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Pinckney, and John Jay) in the House of Representatives.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1800-united-states-presidential-election] With these votes, the total number of votes for Jefferson and Burr was 73, which gave them a majority of the total, but they were tied.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Holly Brewer, a legal historian, argued that the counting of the Georgia ballot did not support Ackerman and Fontana's theory.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Brewer's arguments helped to influence Vice President Pence's decision to reject the theory that he had such powers, via Judge J.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Jefferson and Burr carried every state that had supported the Democratic-Republicans in 1796, made gains in Maryland, and picked up Burr's home state of New York.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1800-united-states-presidential-election] In the six states choosing electors by some form of popular vote, they won a landslide over Adams and Pinckney, polling 15,846 more votes than the Federalist ticket.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Adams made gains in Pennsylvania and North Carolina, but these votes were not enough to offset the Democratic-Republican gains elsewhere.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Of the 155 counties and independent cities making returns, Jefferson and Burr won in 115 (74.19%), whereas the Adams ticket carried 40 (25.81%).
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1800-united-states-presidential-election] This was the last time that Vermont voted for the Federalists and the last time a Federalist won electoral votes from Pennsylvania.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1800-united-states-presidential-election] This was the first of two elections contested between people who would at some point serve as vice president, the other being 1968.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Of the 16 states that took part in the 1800 election, six (Kentucky, Maryland, North Carolina, Rhode Island, Tennessee, and Virginia) used some kind of popular vote.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1800-united-states-presidential-election] In Rhode Island and Virginia, voters elected their state's entire Electoral College delegation at large; Kentucky, Maryland, North Carolina, and Tennessee all used some variation of single-member districts.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1800-united-states-presidential-election] In the rest, electors were chosen by the state legislature.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Not until the 1836 presidential election would all states have direct popular selection of electors (except South Carolina, which had its state legislature vote for electors until 1868).
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Popular vote records for several states are incomplete, and the returns from Kentucky and Tennessee appear to have been lost; states did not print or issue electoral ballots, and most were issued by newspapers that supported a particular party or candidate.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Newspapers are also the main source of voting records in the early 19th century, and frontier states such as Tennessee had few in operation, without any known surviving examples.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Kentucky, Maryland, North Carolina, and Tennessee chose each of their electors from specially-drawn single-member districts, the results from which are as follows.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1800-united-states-presidential-election] In February 1801, the members of the House of Representatives balloted as states to determine whether Jefferson or Burr would become president.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1800-united-states-presidential-election] There were sixteen states, each with one vote; an absolute majority of nine was required for victory.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1800-united-states-presidential-election] It was the outgoing House of Representatives, controlled by the Federalist Party, that was charged with electing the new president.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Jefferson was the great enemy of the Federalists, and a faction of Federalist representatives tried to block him and elect Burr.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Most Federalists voted for Burr, giving Burr six of the eight states controlled by Federalists.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1800-united-states-presidential-election] The seven delegations controlled by Democratic-Republicans all voted for Jefferson, and Georgia's sole Federalist representative also voted for him, giving him eight states.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1800-united-states-presidential-election] The Vermont delegation was evenly split and cast a blank ballot.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1800-united-states-presidential-election] The remaining state, Maryland, had five Federalist representatives to three Democratic-Republicans; one of its Federalist representatives voted for Jefferson, forcing that state delegation also to cast a blank ballot.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Publicly, Burr remained quiet between mid-December 1800 and mid-February 1801, when the electoral votes were counted.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Behind the scenes, he faced mounting pressure from within the party to step aside if he and Jefferson should tie in electoral votes.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Regardless, he refused to disavow the presidency, writing in December 1800 to Representative Samuel Smith (R-MD) that he would not "engage to resign" if chosen president, adding that the question was "unnecessary, unreasonable and impertinent".
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Rumors circulated that Representative James A.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Bayard (F-DE) had—purportedly in Burr's name—approached Smith and Edward Livingston (R-NY) with offers of political appointments if they voted for Burr.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Neither came to pass, however, chiefly due to Hamilton's energetic opposition to Burr.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Hamilton embarked on a frenzied letter-writing campaign to get Federalist Representatives to support Jefferson because he was "by far not so dangerous a man" as Burr; in short, he would much rather have someone with wrong principles than someone devoid of any.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1800-united-states-presidential-election] From February 11 to 17, the House cast a total of 35 ballots; each time eight state delegations voted for Jefferson, one short of the necessary majority of nine.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1800-united-states-presidential-election] On February 17, on the 36th ballot, Bayard changed his vote from Burr to no selection, joined by his allies in Maryland and Vermont.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1800-united-states-presidential-election] This changed the Maryland and Vermont votes from no selection to Jefferson, giving him the votes of 10 states and the presidency.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1800-united-states-presidential-election] The four representatives present from South Carolina, all Federalists, also changed their 3–1 selection of Burr to four abstentions.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Due to the experiences of this and the previous election, sentiment for a new way of selecting the president and vice president rose significantly, resulting in the Twelfth Amendment.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1800-united-states-presidential-election] The Constitution, in Article II, Section 1, provided that the state legislatures should decide the manner in which their electors were chosen.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1800-united-states-presidential-election] In the 2015 musical *Hamilton* by Lin Manuel Miranda, the contest between Jefferson and Burr is recounted in "The Election of 1800".
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1800-united-states-presidential-election] The song focuses on Alexander Hamilton's role in deciding the outcome of the 1801 contingent election.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1800-united-states-presidential-election] The musical simplifies the complicated multiple elections somewhat, portraying Adams's unpopularity as making the real choice between Jefferson and Burr.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Historians wrote that Adams did not lose that badly in the original election, with the musical inflating the size of Jefferson's victory.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1800-united-states-presidential-election] It implies Hamilton's support for Jefferson over Burr was the catalyst for the Burr–Hamilton duel; in fact, while that helped sour relations between Burr and Hamilton, the duel was ultimately provoked by Hamilton's statements about Burr in the 1804 New York gubernatorial election.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] Presidential elections were held in the United States on November 2, 1880.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] Garfield defeated Winfield Scott Hancock of the Democratic Party.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] After the longest convention in the party's history, the factionalized Republicans chose Representative Garfield of Ohio as their standard-bearer.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] The Democratic Party chose Major General Winfield Scott Hancock of Pennsylvania as their nominee.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] The dominance of the two major parties began to fray as an upstart left-wing party, the Greenback Party, nominated another Civil War general for president, Iowa Congressman James B.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] In a campaign fought mainly over issues of Civil War loyalties, tariffs, and Chinese immigration, Garfield narrowly won both the electoral and popular vote.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] He and Hancock each took just over 48 percent of the popular vote, while Weaver and two other minor candidates, Neal Dow and John W.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] In the end, the popular vote totals of the two main candidates were separated by 1,898 votes (0.11%), the smallest victory in the national popular vote ever recorded.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] In the electoral college, however, Garfield's victory was much larger; he won the tipping point state of New York by 21,033 votes (1.91%).
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] Hancock's sweep of the Southern states was not enough for victory, but it cemented his party's dominance of the region for generations.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] This was the first election in which people in every state were able to vote directly for presidential electors, and the voter turnout rate was one of the highest in the nation's history.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] This was the last of six consecutive presidential election victories for the Republican Party.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] Garfield was assassinated during his first year in office, and he was succeeded by his vice president, Chester A.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] The two major parties were the Republicans and the Democrats, and after the end of the Reconstruction Era in 1877, the national electorate was closely divided between them.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] Party membership was only partly based on ideology; party identification often reflected ethnic and religious background, as well as Civil War loyalties that were still keenly felt by many voters.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] Most Northern Protestants voted Republican, as did black Southerners.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] On the other hand, white Southerners and Northern Catholics generally voted Democratic.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] The gold standard and the tariff tax on imports divided the major parties.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] The monetary debate was over the basis for the value of the United States dollar.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] Nothing but gold and silver coin had ever been legal tender in the United States until the Civil War, when the mounting costs of the war forced the United States Congress to issue "greenbacks" (dollar bills backed by government bonds).
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] Greenbacks helped pay for the war, but resulted in severe inflation .
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] After the war, bondholders and other creditors (based in the North) wanted to return to a gold standard.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] At the same time, debtors (especially in the South and West) benefited from the way inflation reduced the real value of their debts, and workers and some businessmen liked the way inflation made for easy credit.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] Monetary debate intensified as Congress effectively demonetized silver in 1873 and began redeeming greenbacks in gold by 1879, while limiting their circulation.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] As the 1880 election season began, the nation's money was backed by gold alone, but the issue was far from settled.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] Tariff policy was a major source of party conflict in late 19th-century and early 20th-century America.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] During the Civil War, Congress raised protective tariffs to new heights.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] This was done partly to pay for the war, but partly because high tariffs were popular in the North.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] A high tariff meant that foreign goods were more expensive, which made it easier for American businesses to sell goods domestically.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] Republicans supported high tariffs as a way to protect American jobs and increase prosperity.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] Democrats condemned them as a source of higher prices for goods, whereas the higher revenues that they generated for the federal government were not needed after the conclusion of the Civil War.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] However Northern Democrats from manufacturing districts, especially in Pennsylvania, also supported high tariffs.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] In the interest of party unity, the leaders of each party often sought to avoid the question as much as possible.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] In the election of 1876, Republican Rutherford B.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] Hayes of Ohio defeated Democrat Samuel J.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] Tilden of New York in one of the most hotly contested presidential elections in the nation's history.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] The early results indicated a Democratic victory, but the electoral votes of several Southern states were disputed bitterly.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] Both parties in Congress agreed to convene a bipartisan Electoral Commission, which ultimately decided the race for Hayes.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] For Democrats, the "stolen election" became a rallying cry, and the Democratic majority in the House of Representatives spent much of 1878 investigating it, although they failed to turn up any new evidence against their Republican foes.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] At first, Tilden was seen as the front-runner for the 1880 nomination.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] For leading Republicans, Hayes's inauguration in 1877 signaled the start of backroom maneuverings for the nomination in 1880.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] Even before his election, Hayes had pledged not to run for a second term, leaving the path to the White House open in 1880.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] His cabinet selections alienated many party leaders as well, deepening the growing divide within the Republican party between forces loyal to New York Senator Roscoe Conkling and those loyal to Maine Senator James G.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] The parties agreed on their respective platforms and nominees at conventions, which met in the summer before the election.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] The Republican convention met first, convening in Chicago, Illinois, on June 2.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] The three strongest candidates leading up to the convention were former president Ulysses S.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] Blaine and Treasury Secretary John Sherman.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] Grant was seeking an unprecedented third term, and was backed by Conkling's faction of the Republican Party, known as the Stalwarts.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] They were mainly known for their support of the spoils system and opposition to the civil service reforms sought by President Hayes.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] Blaine, a senator and former representative from Maine, was backed by the Half-Breed faction of the party, which supported civil service reform.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] Sherman, the brother of Civil War general William Tecumseh Sherman, was a former representative and senator from Ohio.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] He was backed by a smaller delegation that supported neither of the major factions.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] With 379 votes required for nomination, on the first ballot Grant received 304, Blaine 285, and Sherman 93.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] Through successive ballots, none of the candidates were close to victory, so the voting continued.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] After the thirty-fifth ballot, Blaine and Sherman delegates switched their support to a "dark horse", Representative James A.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] Garfield from Ohio, who was in attendance as a Sherman supporter.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] On the next ballot, Garfield won the nomination with 399 votes.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] To placate the Grant faction, Garfield's Ohio supporters suggested Levi P.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] Morton declined, based on Conkling's advice.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] They next offered the nomination to Chester A.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] Conkling also advised him to decline, but he accepted.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] He was nominated, and the longest-ever Republican National Convention adjourned on June 8, 1880.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] Later that month, the Democrats held their convention in Cincinnati, Ohio.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] Six men were officially candidates, and several others also received votes.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] The leading candidates were Major General Winfield Scott Hancock from Pennsylvania and Senator Thomas F.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] Tilden was not officially a candidate, but wielded heavy influence over the convention.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] However, he was ambiguous about his willingness to participate in another campaign, leading some supporters to defect.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] While Hancock and Bayard were the leading candidates, some delegates backed men they saw as Tilden surrogates, including Henry B.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] Payne from Ohio, an attorney and former congressman, and Samuel J.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] Randall from Pennsylvania, the Speaker of the United States House of Representatives.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] The first ballot was inconclusive, with Hancock and Bayard leading the count, but neither close to winning.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] Before the second round, Tilden's withdrawal became known for certain; delegates then shifted to Hancock, who was nominated.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] William Hayden English, a conservative politician and businessman from the swing state of Indiana, was nominated for vice president.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] The Greenback Party convention gathered in Chicago in mid-June, using the hall recently vacated by the Republicans.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] The party was a newcomer to the political scene in 1880, having arisen as a response to the economic depression that followed the Panic of 1873, mostly in the nation's West and South.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] During the Civil War, Congress had authorized "greenbacks", a form of money redeemable in government bonds, rather than in gold, as was traditional.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] After the war, many Democrats and Republicans in the East sought to return to the gold standard, and the government began to withdraw greenbacks from circulation.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] The reduction of the money supply, combined with the economic depression, made life harder for debtors, farmers, and industrial laborers; the Greenback Party hoped to draw support from these groups.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] Beyond their support for a larger money supply, they also favored an eight-hour work day, safety regulations in factories, and an end to child labor.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] Six men were candidates for the Greenback nomination.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] Weaver, an Iowa congressman and Civil War general, was the clear favorite, but two other congressmen, Benjamin F.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] Butler from Massachusetts and Hendrick B.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] Wright from Pennsylvania, also commanded considerable followings.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] Weaver triumphed quickly, winning a majority of the 850 delegates' votes on the first ballot.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] Chambers, a Texas businessman and Confederate veteran, was likewise nominated for vice president on the initial vote.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] More tumultuous was the fight over the platform, as delegates from disparate factions of the left-wing movement clashed over women's suffrage, Chinese immigration, and the extent to which the government should regulate working conditions.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] A convention of the Prohibition Party also met that month in Cleveland, Ohio.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] The Prohibitionists, more of a movement than a party, focused their efforts on banning alcohol.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] Most party members came from pietist churches, and most were former Republicans.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] Only twelve states sent delegates to the convention, and the platform they agreed on was silent on most issues of the day, focusing instead on the supposed evils of alcohol.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] For president, the Prohibitionists nominated Neal Dow, a Civil War general from Maine.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] As mayor of Portland, Dow helped to pass the "Maine law", which banned the sale of alcohol in the city; it became the model for temperance laws around the country.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] Finally, a revived Anti-Masonic Party nominated John W.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] Phelps, another Civil War general, on a platform of opposition to Freemasonry.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] Political prognosticators gave Weaver little chance of victory, and Dow and Phelps none at all.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] James Abram Garfield was raised in humble circumstances on an Ohio farm by his widowed mother.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] He worked at various jobs, including on a canal boat, in his youth.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] Beginning at age 17, he studied at Williams College in Williamstown, Massachusetts, from which he graduated in 1856.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] A year later, Garfield entered politics as a Republican.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] He married Lucretia Rudolph in 1858, and served as a member of the Ohio State Senate (1859–1861).
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] Garfield opposed Confederate secession, served as a major general in the Union Army during the Civil War, and fought in the battles of Middle Creek, Shiloh, and Chickamauga.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] He was first elected to Congress in 1862 to represent Ohio's 19th District.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] Throughout Garfield's extended congressional service after the Civil War, he firmly supported the gold standard and gained a reputation as a skilled orator.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] Garfield initially agreed with Radical Republican views regarding Reconstruction, but later favored a moderate approach for civil rights enforcement for freedmen.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] After his nomination, Garfield met with party leaders in an attempt to heal the schism between the Stalwarts and Half-Breeds.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] In his formal letter to the party accepting his nomination, written with advice from party leaders, he endorsed the ideas of high tariffs and sound money, but drew particular attention to the issues of Chinese immigration and civil service reform.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] On both, Garfield sought a moderate path.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] He called for some restrictions on the former, through treaty renegotiation with the Chinese government.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] He straddled the divide on civil service reform, saying that he agreed with the concept, while promising to make no appointments without consulting party leaders, a position 20th-century biographer Allan Peskin called "inconsistent".
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] As was traditional at the time, Garfield conducted a "front porch campaign", returning to his home for the duration of the contest, and leaving the actual campaigning to surrogates.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] Winfield Scott Hancock was born and raised in Pennsylvania.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] He was named for General Winfield Scott, a war hero in the War of 1812 and Whig Party presidential candidate in the 1852 election.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] He attended the United States Military Academy at West Point and served in the Army for four decades, including service in the Mexican–American War and as a Union general in the Civil War.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] Known to his Army colleagues as "Hancock the Superb", he was noted in particular for his personal leadership at the Battle of Gettysburg in 1863, where he led the defense of Pickett's Charge, getting wounded in the process.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] His military service continued after the Civil War, as Hancock participated in the military Reconstruction of the South and the Army's presence at the Western frontier.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] During Reconstruction, he sided with then-President Andrew Johnson in working for a quick end to military occupation of the South and a return to government by the pre-war establishment.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] Hancock's reputation as a war hero at Gettysburg, combined with his status as a prominent Democrat with impeccable Unionist credentials and pro-states' rights views, made him a quadrennial presidential possibility.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] Hancock was officially notified of his nomination in July, and responded with the traditional letter of acceptance.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] As Garfield had, the Democratic nominee sought to cause no controversy in his statement, which according to biographer David M.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] After scorning the previous years of Republican rule, Hancock sought to tamp down fears that election of a Democrat would overturn the results of the war and Reconstruction, a common Republican campaign theme.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] Unlike Garfield, Hancock had no record in elected office, but the acceptance letter gave no further indication of his political preferences.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] Hancock remained on active duty during the campaign at his post on Governors Island in New York Harbor.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] James Baird Weaver was born in Ohio, and moved to Iowa as a boy when his family claimed a homestead on the frontier.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] He became politically active as a young man and was an advocate for farmers and laborers, joining and quitting several political parties in the furtherance of the progressive causes in which he believed.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] After serving in the Union Army in the Civil War, Weaver returned to Iowa and worked for the election of Republican candidates.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] After making several unsuccessful attempts at Republican nominations to various offices, and growing dissatisfied with the conservative wing of the party, in 1877 Weaver switched to the Greenback Party, advocating an increased money supply and stricter regulation of big business.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] As a Greenbacker with Democratic support, Weaver won election to the House of Representatives in 1878.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] Unlike the major party candidates, Weaver planned to take the field himself, giving speeches around the country.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] His running mate, Chambers, was to do the same, until a fall from a train in July disabled him for the duration of the campaign.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] As the Greenbackers had the only ticket that included a Southerner, he hoped to make inroads in that region.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] Weaver's path to victory, already unlikely, was made more difficult by his refusal to run a fusion ticket in states where Democratic and Greenbacker strength might have combined to outvote the Republicans.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] His party's message of racial inclusion also presaged difficulty in the South, as the Greenbackers would face the same obstacles the Republicans did in the face of increasing black disenfranchisement.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] Hancock and the Democrats expected to carry the Solid South, while much of the North was considered safe territory for Garfield and the Republicans; most of the campaign would involve a handful of close states, including New York and Indiana.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] National elections were largely decided in close elections in New York and the Midwest.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] With fifteen years having passed since the end of the war, and Union generals at the head of all of the major and minor party tickets, the appeal to wartime loyalties was of diminishing value in exciting the voters.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] The Democrats, for their part, campaigned on the character of the candidates.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] They attacked Garfield for his connection with the Crédit Mobilier of America scandal of the early 1870s, in which many members of Congress were bribed by the Crédit Mobilier corporation, a railroad construction company.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] Garfield's precise involvement was unknown, but modern biographers agree that his account of his dealings with the construction syndicate were less than perfectly honest.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] Democrats used the incident as a contrast with Hancock who, as a career army officer, stood apart from Congress and lobbyists.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] Many in the Republican Party were reluctant to directly criticize the "hero of Gettysburg", but they did characterize Hancock as uninformed on the issues, and some of his former comrades-in-arms gave critical speeches regarding his character.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] Democrats never made clear what about their victory would improve the nation; Jordan later characterized their message as simply "our man is better than your man".
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] The Greenbackers saw the impact of Civil War loyalties more acutely as they vied for Southern votes.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] Weaver embarked on a speaking tour of the South in July and August.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] Although the local Greenback parties had seen some recent success, the national party, with an ex-Republican Union general at the head of the ticket, faced more opposition.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] The party's courtship of black voters, too, threatened the white Democratic establishment, leading to violent outbursts at Weaver's rallies and threats against his supporters.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] As Weaver campaigned in the North in September and October, Republicans accused him of purposely dividing the vote to help Democrats win a plurality in marginal states.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] Weaver refused to cooperate with Democrats in running fusion slates of presidential electors.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] However, in state-level races, Greenback candidates did often combine with Democrats to defeat Republican candidates.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] In the September gubernatorial race in Maine, one such fusion ticket nominated Harris M.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] Plaisted, who narrowly defeated the incumbent Republican in what was thought to be a safe state for that party.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] The surprise defeat sent a shock through the Garfield campaign, and caused them to rethink their strategy of waving the bloody shirt.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] After their defeat in Maine, the Republicans began to emphasize policy differences more.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] One significant difference between them and the Democrats was the plank in the Democratic platform endorsing "a tariff for revenue only".
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] That is the tariff would only be used to cover the costs of the federal government, and not be raised higher to help specific industries.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] Garfield's campaigners used this statement to paint the Democrats as unsympathetic to the plight of industrial laborers, a group that benefited from a high protective tariff.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] The tariff issue cut Democratic support in industrialized Northern states, which were essential in establishing a Democratic majority.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] Hancock made the situation worse when, attempting to strike a moderate stance, he said "the tariff question is a local question".
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] While not completely inaccurate—tariff preferences often reflected local concerns—the statement was at odds with the Democrats' platform and suggested that Hancock did not understand the issue.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] The change in tactics appeared to be effective, as October state elections in Ohio and Indiana resulted in Republican victories there, discouraging Democrats about their chances the following month.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] Democratic party leaders had selected English as Hancock's running mate because of his popularity in Indiana.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] With their state-level defeat there, some talked of dropping English from the ticket, but he convinced them that the October losses owed more to local issues, and that the Democratic ticket could still carry Indiana, if not Ohio, in November.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] In the last weeks before the election, the issue of Chinese immigration entered the race.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] Both major parties (as well as the Greenbackers) pledged in their platforms to limit immigration from China, which native-born workers in the Western states believed was depressing their wages.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] On October 20, however, a Democratic newspaper published a letter, purportedly from Garfield to a group of businessmen, pledging to keep immigration at the current levels so that industry could keep workers' wages low.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] Garfield denounced the letter as a ruse, but not before one hundred thousand copies of the newspaper were mailed to California and Oregon.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] Once the letter was exposed as a forgery, Garfield biographer Peskin believes it may even have gained votes for the Republican in the East, but it likely weakened him in the West.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] 36.2% of the voting age population and 80.6% of eligible voters participated in the election.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] The extremely close election, with very high turnout, reflected the typical pattern of the Gilded Age.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] Democrats were assured of a Solid South electoral vote, as well as most of the border states.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] Republicans captured the Northeast and Midwest, winning the critical swing states of New York, Ohio, and Indiana.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] The Republicans captured the electoral vote 214–155, but the popular vote margin was under 2000 out of over 9 million votes cast.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] Republicans won the House of Representatives 147–135, but the Senate was evenly split, with the vice president casting the deciding vote.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] When all the ballots were counted, fewer than 2,000 votes separated Garfield and Hancock, the closest popular vote of any American presidential election before or since.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] The voters showed their interest in the election by turning out in record numbers; 78 percent of eligible voters cast a ballot, among largest percentages in American history.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] Each major party candidate earned just over 48 percent of the vote.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] Weaver won more than 3 percent, tripling the Greenback total of four years earlier.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] The other minor party candidates fared far worse, as Dow and Phelps earned 0.1 and 0.01 percent, respectively.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] Garfield carried the crucial state of New York by 20,000 votes out of 1.1 million cast there.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] Other states were much closer; Hancock's margin of victory in California was only about 144 votes.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] In the electoral college, the vote was more decisive.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] As expected, Hancock carried the South and border states, but Garfield swept all but one of the Northern states (the exception was New Jersey, which he lost by just two thousand votes).
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] Both candidates carried nineteen states, but Garfield's triumphs in the more populous North translated into a 214–155 electoral college victory.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] This is one of three times that both candidates won the same number of states, along with 1848 and 2020.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] The sectional divide of the vote further spurred the Republicans' retreat from the South after Reconstruction and demonstrated that they could win without competing there.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] Weaver's resistance to fusion had no effect on the result; the combined Democratic and Greenback vote would have carried Indiana, but not any other of the states Garfield won, and the result would still have been a Republican majority in the electoral college.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] Hancock was convinced that the Republicans won New York by fraud.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] Lacking evidence, and mindful of the turmoil caused by the disputed election four years earlier, the Democrats did not pursue the matter.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] California voted for a losing Democrat for the first time ever, which would not occur again until 2000.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] Republicans would not win without New Jersey and Delaware until 2000.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] Nevada also voted for a losing Democrat for the first time.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] Furthermore, this is the only time since the admission of California that a candidate has won nationally without winning either California or Texas.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] 15.12% of Garfield's votes came from the eleven states of the former Confederacy, with him taking 37.47% of the vote in that region.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] Morgan Kousser, a majority of Black men voted in 9 of the 11 Southern states in the 1880 presidential election.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] In only two states it was under 50% --Georgia with 39% of Blacks voting and Mississippi with 34%.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] In Arkansas, Florida, Louisiana, North Carolina, Tennessee, and Texas, Black turnout was higher than white turnout.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] Turnout was the same in Alabama and Virginia.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] In Virginia, a split in the Democratic Party over the payment of state debts led to two Democratic electoral slates being nominated, one by the regular debt-paying "Funder" Democrats, the other by the "Readjuster" or anti-debt paying faction of the party.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] Both slates were pledged to the Hancock ticket.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] Republicans initially hoped the split could lead Garfield to win the state, but the results were otherwise.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] The Readjuster ticket received 31,527 votes, but the Funder Democrats took 96,449 votes, enough to defeat the Republicans, whose slate had 84,020.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] Although Hancock won Georgia's popular vote easily, there was an irregularity in that state's electoral votes.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] However, Georgia's electors failed to cast their ballots on December 1, instead voting on the following Wednesday, December 8.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] Congress chose to count Georgia's vote in the official tally anyway; had they not done so, Hancock's electoral vote would have been 144, not 155.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] At the time, voters in California voted for individual electors, with the top six candidates being elected.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] One of the electors on the Democratic ticket was David S.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] Terry, a controversial figure in California politics due to his killing of David C.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] As a result, about five hundred Democratic voters scratched Terry's name off of their ballots.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] Due to the closeness of the election, these lost votes caused Terry to receive fewer votes than the entire Republican ticket and thus a single Republican elector won the sixth-most votes to claim the last elector position.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] This was the first occasion in which California's electoral vote was split, rather than being awarded to a single candidate.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] This would subsequently occur in California three additional times in 1892, 1896, and 1912.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] As Garfield entered office in March 1881, the Republican party schism that had been patched up for the election tore apart once more.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] Garfield appointed Blaine to the cabinet, and Conkling's Stalwart faction became irked at their lack of control over patronage, even in Conkling's home state of New York.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] Robertson, a civil service reform supporter, to the most lucrative government post in New York, and refused to withdraw the nomination despite Conkling's protests; in response, Conkling and his allies brought all legislative action in the closely divided Senate to a halt.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] In May, Conkling and fellow New York Senator Thomas C.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] Platt resigned from the Senate in protest.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] The two Stalwarts expected the New York legislature to reelect them in triumph; instead, the legislature deadlocked for months, eventually declining to return either man to the Senate.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] Before that result was known, however, Charles Guiteau, a mentally unstable man angry about not receiving a patronage appointment, shot Garfield in Washington, D.C., on July 2, 1881.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] Garfield lingered for 2+1⁄2 months before dying on September 19, 1881.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] Arthur, the New York Stalwart, was sworn in as president that night.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] Garfield's murder by a spoilsman inspired the nation to reform the civil service—and Arthur, erstwhile member of the Conkling machine, joined the cause.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] In 1883, a bipartisan majority in Congress passed the Pendleton Civil Service Reform Act to reform the worst of the office-seeking system, and Arthur signed the measure into law.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] Congress also settled the issue of Chinese immigration, passing the Chinese Exclusion Act in 1882.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] Arthur initially vetoed a similar measure, which he believed contradicted the United States' treaty with China, but eventually signed a compromise bill, which banned immigration from China for ten years.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] Tariffs, a major issue in the campaign, remained largely unchanged in the four years that followed, although Congress did pass a minor revision that reduced them by an average of less than 2 percent.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1880-united-states-presidential-election] After a half-hearted attempt at the nomination in 1884, Arthur retired and died two years later.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1912-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Presidential elections were held in the United States on November 5, 1912.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1912-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Roosevelt served as president from 1901 to 1909 as a Republican, and Taft succeeded him with his support.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1912-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Taft's conservatism angered Roosevelt, so he challenged Taft for the party nomination at the 1912 Republican National Convention.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1912-united-states-presidential-election-p01] When Taft and his conservative allies narrowly prevailed, Roosevelt rallied his progressive supporters and launched a third-party bid.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1912-united-states-presidential-election-p01] At the Democratic Convention, Wilson won the presidential nomination on the 46th ballot, defeating Speaker of the House Champ Clark and several other candidates with the support of William Jennings Bryan and other progressive Democrats.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1912-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The Socialist Party renominated its perennial standard-bearer, Eugene V.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1912-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The general election was bitterly contested by Wilson, Roosevelt, Taft and Debs.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1912-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Roosevelt's "New Nationalism" platform called for social insurance programs, reduction to an eight-hour workday, and robust federal regulation of the economy.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1912-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Wilson's "New Freedom" platform called for tariff reduction, banking reform, and new antitrust regulation.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1912-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Incumbent Taft conducted a subdued campaign based on his platform of "progressive conservatism".
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1912-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The Republican split enabled Wilson to win 40 states and a landslide victory in the electoral college with just 41.8% of the popular vote, the lowest vote share for a victorious presidential candidate since 1860.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1912-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Roosevelt finished second with 88 electoral votes and 27.4% of the popular vote.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1912-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Taft took 23.2% of the national vote and carried two states, Vermont and Utah; he won the lowest share of the popular vote of any Republican nominee in history.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1912-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Debs, the fourth-place finisher, won no electoral votes but received 6% of the popular vote, which remains the highest percentage of the vote ever won by a Socialist candidate in the history of American presidential elections.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1912-united-states-presidential-election-p01] In this election, more than one third of voters cast third-party votes, the greatest percentage of votes to have ever been cast for third-party candidates in an American presidential election.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1912-united-states-presidential-election-p01] This was the last U.S. presidential election to date in which the second-placed candidate was neither a Republican nor a Democrat.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1912-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Republican president Theodore Roosevelt had declined to run for re-election in 1908 in fulfillment of a pledge to the American people not to seek a third term.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1912-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Roosevelt had tapped Secretary of War William Howard Taft to become his successor, and Taft defeated William Jennings Bryan in the 1908 general election.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1912-united-states-presidential-election-p01] During Taft's administration, a rift developed between Roosevelt and Taft, and they became the leaders of the Republican Party's two wings: progressives led by Roosevelt and conservatives led by Taft.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1912-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Progressives favored labor restrictions protecting women and children, promoted ecological conservation, and were more sympathetic toward labor unions.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1912-united-states-presidential-election-p01] They also favored the popular election of federal and state judges over appointment by the president or governors.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1912-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Conservatives supported high tariffs to encourage domestic production, but favored business leaders over labor unions and were generally opposed to the popular election of judges.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1912-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Cracks in the party began to show when Taft supported the Payne–Aldrich Tariff Act in 1909.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1912-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The Act favored the industrial Northeast and angered the Northwest and South, where demand was strong for tariff reductions.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1912-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Early in his term, President Taft had promised to stand for a lower tariff bill, but protectionism had been a major policy of the Republican Party since its founding.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1912-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Taft also fought against Roosevelt's antitrust policy.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1912-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Roosevelt distinguished "good trusts" from "bad trusts", for which he had been lambasted.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1912-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Taft argued that all monopolies must be broken up.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1912-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Taft also fired popular conservationist Gifford Pinchot as head of the Bureau of Forestry in 1910.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1912-united-states-presidential-election-p01] By 1910, the split within the party was deep, and Roosevelt and Taft turned against one another despite their personal friendship.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1912-united-states-presidential-election-p01] In that summer Roosevelt began a national speaking tour, during which he outlined his progressive philosophy and the New Nationalist platform, which he introduced in a speech in Osawatomie, Kansas, on August 31.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1912-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Another source of tension involved the authority of the nation's courts, especially the Supreme Court.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1912-united-states-presidential-election-p01] As early as 1910, Roosevelt had begun criticizing certain court decisions, such as *Lochner v.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1912-united-states-presidential-election-p01] New York* (1905), and those jurists whom he dubbed "fossilized judges." He believed that the Supreme Court was interpreting the due process clause of the 14th Amendment and the doctrine of "freedom of contract" to forestall necessary reform legislation, such as the limiting of work hours.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1912-united-states-presidential-election-p01] He, as well as more populist progressives like William Jennings Bryan in the Democratic Party, came out in favor of an amendment to allow the recall of judges and, possibly, judicial decisions.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1912-united-states-presidential-election-p01] This outraged Taft (a former judge and future Supreme Court Chief Justice) and other constitutional conservatives, like Elihu Root and Alton B.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1912-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Taft considered Roosevelt a danger to constitutional government and resolved to resist his eventual challenge for the Republican nomination.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1912-united-states-presidential-election-p01] In the 1910 midterm elections, the Republicans lost 57 seats in the House of Representatives as the Democrats gained a majority for the first time since 1894.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1912-united-states-presidential-election-p01] These results were a large defeat for the conservative wing of the party.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1912-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Campbell writes that one cause may have been a large number of progressive voters choosing third-party candidates over conservative Republicans.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1912-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Roosevelt continued to reject calls to run for president into 1911.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1912-united-states-presidential-election-p01] However, speculation continued, further harming Roosevelt and Taft's relationship.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1912-united-states-presidential-election-p01] For the first time, many convention delegates were elected in presidential preference primaries.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1912-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Progressive Republicans advocated primary elections as a way of breaking the control of political parties by bosses.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1912-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Altogether, 12 states held Republican primaries.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1912-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Senator Robert "Fighting Bob" La Follette won two of the first four primaries (North Dakota and his home state of Wisconsin), but Taft won a major victory in Roosevelt's home state of New York and continued to rack up delegates in more conservative, traditional state conventions.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1912-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Beginning with a runaway victory in Illinois on April 9, Roosevelt won 9 of the last 10 presidential primaries (including Taft's home state of Ohio), losing only Massachusetts.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1912-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Taft also had support from the bulk of the Southern Republican organizations.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1912-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Delegates from the former Confederate states supported Taft by a 5 to 1 margin.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1912-united-states-presidential-election-p01] These states had voted solidly Democratic in every presidential election since 1880, and Roosevelt objected that they were given one-quarter of the delegates when they would contribute nothing to a Republican victory.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1912-united-states-presidential-election-p01] For the Republican National Convention, held June 18–22 in Chicago, 388 delegates were selected through the primaries and Roosevelt won 281 delegates, Taft received 71 delegates, and La Follette received 36 delegates.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1912-united-states-presidential-election-p01] However, Taft had a 566–466 margin, placing him over the 540 needed for nomination, with the delegations selected at state conventions.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1912-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Roosevelt accused the Taft faction of having over 200 fraudulently selected delegates.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1912-united-states-presidential-election-p01] However, the Republican National Committee ruled in favor of Taft for 233 of the delegate cases while 6 were in favor of Roosevelt.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1912-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The committee reinvestigated the 92 of the contested delegates and ruled in favor of Taft for all of them.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1912-united-states-presidential-election-p01] However, Roosevelt had rejected an attempt to abolish delegations from the south at the 1908 Republican National Convention due to him needing them for Taft's nomination.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1912-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Hadley served as Roosevelt's floor manager at the convention.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1912-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Hadley made a motion for 74 of Taft's delegates to be replaced by 72 delegates after the reading of the convention call, but his motion was ruled out of order.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1912-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Elihu Root, a supporter of Taft, was selected to chair the convention after winning 558 votes against McGovern's 501 votes.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1912-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Root was accused of having won through the rotten boroughs of the southern delegations as every northern state, except for four, voted for McGovern.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1912-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Roosevelt broke with tradition and attended the convention, where he was welcomed with great support from voters.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1912-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Despite Roosevelt's presence in Chicago and his attempts to disqualify Taft supporters, the incumbent ticket of Taft and James S.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1912-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Sherman was renominated on the first ballot.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1912-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Sherman was the first sitting vice president re-nominated since John C.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1912-united-states-presidential-election-p01] After losing the vote, Roosevelt announced the formation of a new party dedicated "to the service of all the people." This would later come to be known as the Progressive Party.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1912-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Roosevelt announced that his party would hold its convention in Chicago and that he would accept their nomination if offered.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1912-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Meanwhile, Taft decided not to campaign before the election beyond his acceptance speech on August 1.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1912-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Harding presented Taft's name for the nomination.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1912-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Taft won the nomination while 344 of Roosevelt's delegates abstained from the vote.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1912-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Henry Justin Allen read a speech from Roosevelt in which he criticized the process and stated that delegates had been stolen from his in order to secure Taft's nomination.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1912-united-states-presidential-election-p01] In early 1912, it was widely believed that three-time Democratic presidential candidate William Jennings Bryan would make a fourth attempt to earn the party's nomination, and would likely not have difficulty in earning it.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1912-united-states-presidential-election-p01] However, Bryan announced several months before the convention that he was not interested in another run for the White House.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1912-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Though still seen by many as the Democrats' ideological leader, power shifts within the party in the wake of their success at the 1910 mid-term elections meant that Bryan could no longer be guaranteed the two-thirds majority needed to earn the nomination.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1912-united-states-presidential-election-p01] However, Bryan still had enough followers in the party that he was in a strong position to be the kingmaker at the convention.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1912-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The Democratic National Convention was held in Baltimore from June 25 to July 2.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1912-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Initially, the front-runner was Speaker of the House Champ Clark of Missouri.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1912-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Though Clark received the most votes on early ballots, he was unable to get the two-thirds majority required to win.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1912-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Clark's chances were hurt when Tammany Hall, the powerful New York City Democratic political machine, threw its support behind him.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1912-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The Tammany endorsement caused Bryan to turn against Clark, whom he decried as the candidate of Wall Street, and shift his support to Woodrow Wilson, the reformist Governor of New Jersey.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1912-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Wilson had consistently finished second in balloting, and nearly gave up hope and almost freed his delegates to vote for another candidate.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1912-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Instead, Bryan's defection from Clark to Wilson led many other delegates to do the same.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1912-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Wilson gradually gained strength while Clark's support dwindled, and Wilson finally received the nomination on the 46th ballot.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1912-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Marshall, the governor of Indiana who had swung Indiana's votes to Wilson, was named Wilson's running mate.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1912-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Taft had won the Republican nomination while 344 of Roosevelt's delegates abstained from the vote.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1912-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Later that day supporters of Roosevelt met in the Chicago Orchestra Hall and nominated him as an independent candidate for president which Roosevelt accepted although he requested a formal convention.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1912-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Roosevelt initially considered not running as a third-party candidate until George Walbridge Perkins and Frank Munsey offered their financial support.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1912-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Roosevelt and his supporters formed the Progressive Party at a convention, temporarily chaired by Senator Albert J.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1912-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Beveridge, on August 5, and Hiram Johnson was selected as his vice-presidential running mate.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1912-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Parker had been considered for the presidential nomination, but Parker and Lindsey instead both nominated Johnson for the position.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1912-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The Progressives promised to increase federal regulation and protect the welfare of ordinary people.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1912-united-states-presidential-election-p01] At the convention, Perkins blocked an antitrust plank, shocking reformers who thought of Roosevelt as a true trust-buster.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1912-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The delegates to the convention sang the hymn "Onward, Christian Soldiers" as their anthem.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1912-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Members of the Socialist Party of America had won in multiple elections between the 1908 and 1912 presidential elections with Emil Seidel being elected as the mayor of Milwaukee, Wisconsin, and Victor L.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1912-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Berger was elected to the United States House of Representatives.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1912-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The party claimed that it had 435 members elected to office by 1911, and over one thousand by 1912.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1912-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Dan Hogan put Debs name up for the presidential nomination.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1912-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Debs won the presidential nomination, although he had supported giving the nomination to the *Appeal to Reason'*s editor Fred Warren, with 165 votes while Seidel received 56 votes and Charles Edward Russell received 54 votes.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1912-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Seidel was given the vice-presidential nomination against Russell and Hogan.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1912-united-states-presidential-election-p01] After the presidential ballot Seidel and Russell proposed a motion to make Debs' nomination unanimous and it was accepted.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1912-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Hogan and Slayton proposed to make the nomination of Seidel unanimous after the vice-presidential selection and it was accepted.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1912-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Thompson, who were serving as delegates, voted for Seidel during the presidential balloting.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1912-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Morris Hillquit, Meyer London, and John Spargo, who were serving as delegates, supported Russell during the presidential balloting.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1912-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Hogan, a delegate from Arkansas, had supported Debs during the presidential balloting.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1912-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Mahlon Barnes, who had managed Debs' campaign in the 1908 election, also managed the campaign in 1912.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1912-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The Socialists predicted that they would receive over two million votes and have 12 members elected to Congress, but Debs only received 897,011 votes and Berger lost reelection.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1912-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Debs received his largest number of votes from Ohio while his best percentage was in Nevada.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1912-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The largest percentage gain since the 1908 presidential election was in West Virginia where their vote total increased by over 300%.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1912-united-states-presidential-election-p01] George Brinton McClellan Harvey stated that had Roosevelt not run then Debs would have gained an additional half a million votes.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1912-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The number of Socialists in the state legislatures increased from 20 to 21.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1912-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Roosevelt conducted a vigorous national campaign for the Progressive Party, denouncing the way the Republican nomination had been "stolen".
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1912-united-states-presidential-election-p01] He bundled together his reforms under the rubric of "The New Nationalism" and stumped the country for a strong federal role in regulating the economy and chastising bad corporations.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1912-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Roosevelt rallied progressives with speeches denouncing the political establishment.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1912-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Wilson supported a policy called "The New Freedom".
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1912-united-states-presidential-election-p01] This policy was based mostly on individualism instead of a strong government.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1912-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Wilson opposed Roosevelt's proposal to establish a powerful state bureaucracy charged with regulating large corporations, with Wilson instead favoring the break-up of large corporations in order to create a level economic playing field.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1912-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Though Wilson's rhetoric paid homage to the traditional Democratic Party skepticisms of government and "collectivism", after his election win Wilson would embrace some of the progressive reforms which Roosevelt had campaigned on.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1912-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Taft campaigned quietly and spoke of the need for judges to be more powerful than elected officials.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1912-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The departure of the progressives left the Republican Party firmly controlled by the conservative wing.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1912-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Much of the Republican effort was designed to discredit Roosevelt as a dangerous radical, but this had little effect.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1912-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Many of the nation's pro-Republican newspapers depicted Roosevelt as an egotist running only to spoil Taft's chances and feed his vanity.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1912-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The Socialists had little funding compared to the Republican, Democratic and Progressive campaigns.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1912-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Debs' campaign spent only $66,000, mostly on 3.5 million leaflets and travel to locally organized rallies.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1912-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Debs' biggest event was a speech to 15,000 supporters in New York City.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1912-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Debs claimed that there was no hope under the present decaying capitalist system, and that the worker who votes the Republican or Democratic ticket does worse than throw away his vote, as he is a deserter of his class and becomes his own worst enemy.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1912-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Debs insisted that Democrats, Progressives, and Republicans alike were financed by different factions within the capitalist trusts, and that only the Socialists represented labor.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1912-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Debs condemned "Injunction Bill Taft" and condemned Roosevelt for stealing his socialist clothes with the intent to make socialist policies "safer" for the establishment.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1912-united-states-presidential-election-p01] At a campaign stop in Milwaukee on October 14, John Schrank, a saloonkeeper from New York, shot Roosevelt in the chest.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1912-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The bullet penetrated his steel eyeglass case and a 50-page single-folded copy of his speech *Progressive Cause Greater Than Any Individual* and became lodged in his chest.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1912-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Schrank was immediately disarmed and captured.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1912-united-states-presidential-election-p01] He was suffering from delusion and said the ghost of President McKinley ordered him to kill Roosevelt to prevent a third term.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1912-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Roosevelt shouted for Schrank to remain unharmed and assured the crowd he was all right, then ordered police to take charge of Schrank and ensure no violence was done to him.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1912-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Roosevelt, an experienced hunter and anatomist, correctly concluded that since he was not coughing blood, the bullet had not reached his lung.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1912-united-states-presidential-election-p01] He declined suggestions to go to the hospital and instead delivered his scheduled speech with blood seeping into his shirt.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1912-united-states-presidential-election-p01] His opening comments to the gathered crowd were, "Ladies and gentlemen, I don't know whether you fully understand that I have just been shot, but it takes more than that to kill a bull moose." He spoke for 90 minutes before completing his speech and accepting medical attention.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1912-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Afterward, probes and an x-ray showed that the bullet had lodged in Roosevelt's chest muscle, but did not penetrate the pleura.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1912-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Doctors concluded that it would be less dangerous to leave it in place than to attempt to remove it, and Roosevelt carried the bullet with him for the rest of his life.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1912-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Taft was not campaigning and focused on his presidential duties.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1912-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Wilson briefly suspended his campaigning.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1912-united-states-presidential-election-p01] By October 17, Wilson was back on the campaign trail but avoided any criticism of Roosevelt or his party.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1912-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Roosevelt spent two weeks recuperating before returning to the campaign trail with a major speech on October 30, designed to reassure his supporters he was strong enough for the presidency.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1912-united-states-presidential-election-p01] On October 30, 1912, Vice President James S.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1912-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Sherman died of nephritis, leaving Taft without a running mate less than a week before the election.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1912-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Nicholas Murray Butler, president of Columbia University, was quickly chosen to replace Sherman on the Republican ticket.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1912-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Turnout in the election was 59%, with 27.9% of the voting age population participating in the election.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1912-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Wilson captured the presidency handily by carrying a record 40 states.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1912-united-states-presidential-election-p02] This election saw the lowest turnout among eligible voters since the 1836 presidential election, falling 20 points short of the turnout in the 1896 election.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1912-united-states-presidential-election-p02] The implementation of Jim Crow laws after the Reconstruction Era significantly reduced Black voter turnout.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1912-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Wilson won the presidency with a lower percentage of the popular vote than any candidate since Abraham Lincoln in 1860.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1912-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Taft's result remains the worst performance for any incumbent president, both in terms of electoral votes (8) and share of popular votes (23.17%).
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1912-united-states-presidential-election-p02] His 8 electoral votes remain the fewest by a Republican and by any major-party candidate, matched by Alf Landon's 1936 campaign.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1912-united-states-presidential-election-p02] His 23.17% of the popular vote is the lowest ever for a Republican or any major party nominee.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1912-united-states-presidential-election-p02] This was the first time since 1852 that Iowa, Maine, New Hampshire, Ohio, and Rhode Island voted for a Democrat, and the first time in history that Massachusetts voted Democratic.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1912-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Democrats would not win Maine again until 1964, Connecticut and Delaware until 1936, Illinois, Indiana, Iowa, New Jersey, New York, Oregon, West Virginia, and Wisconsin until 1932, and Massachusetts and Rhode Island until 1928.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1912-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Additionally, it was the last time until 1932 that the Republicans failed to win Michigan, Minnesota and South Dakota.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1912-united-states-presidential-election-p02] This is one of two times since 1852 that Maine and Vermont did not support the same party (the other being in 1968).
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1912-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Theodore Roosevelt's 88 electoral votes and 27.4% of the popular vote are the highest won by a third party in a presidential election.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1912-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Wilson's raw vote total and percentage was less than William Jennings Bryan's total in any of his three campaigns.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1912-united-states-presidential-election-p02] In only two regions, New England and the Pacific, was Wilson's vote greater than the greatest Bryan vote.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1912-united-states-presidential-election-p02] The 1912 election was the first to include all 48 of the current contiguous United States.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1912-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Only 12 of the 48 states saw a candidate win with a majority of the popular vote.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1912-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Wilson won a majority in the 11 former Confederate states.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1912-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Only South Dakota, where Taft did not appear on the ballot, gave Roosevelt a majority.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1912-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Taft won only two states, Vermont and Utah, each with a plurality.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1912-united-states-presidential-election-p02] This is the only time in American history that three people who at some point served as president ran for president in the same election, though in 1920 and 1960 three future presidents ran for either president or vice-president.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1912-united-states-presidential-election-p02] He finished 2nd behind Roosevelt in 5 states, and 2nd behind Taft only in Utah.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1912-united-states-presidential-election-p02] He finished 3rd in 2 states, in Michigan where Roosevelt finished 1st and Taft finished 2nd, and in Vermont where Taft finished 1st and Roosevelt finished 2nd.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1912-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Roosevelt would win the most electoral votes out of any third-party candidate in American history, finishing 1st in 6 states.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1912-united-states-presidential-election-p02] He finished 2nd in 24 states, behind Wilson in 23, and behind Taft in Vermont.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1912-united-states-presidential-election-p02] In 15 of those, Wilson finished 1st and Taft finished 2nd.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1912-united-states-presidential-election-p02] In the other two, Taft finished 1st and Wilson finished 2nd in Utah, while Wilson finished 1st and Debs finished 2nd in Florida.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1912-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Roosevelt was not on the ballot in Oklahoma.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1912-united-states-presidential-election-p02] He finished 2nd in 18 states, behind Wilson in 17 of those.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1912-united-states-presidential-election-p02] The one exception was Michigan where Taft finished 2nd behind Roosevelt.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1912-united-states-presidential-election-p02] In 18 of those, Wilson finished 1st and Roosevelt finished 2nd.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1912-united-states-presidential-election-p02] In the other 3, Minnesota, Pennsylvania, and Washington, Roosevelt finished 1st and Wilson finished 2nd.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1912-united-states-presidential-election-p02] In 4 of those, the top 3 in order were Wilson-Roosevelt-Debs.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1912-united-states-presidential-election-p02] In Florida, Wilson finished 1st, Debs finished 2nd, and Roosevelt finished 3rd.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1912-united-states-presidential-election-p02] While not on the ballot in California, Taft received 3,914 write-in votes in the state, placing him 5th, behind Roosevelt, Wilson, Debs, and Chafin.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1912-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Taft was not on the ballot at all in South Dakota, not even as a write-in option.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1912-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Debs finished 2nd in Florida behind Wilson.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1912-united-states-presidential-election-p02] In Nevada, Arizona, Louisiana and Mississippi, Wilson finished 1st, Roosevelt finished 2nd, Debs finished 3rd and Taft finished 4th.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1912-united-states-presidential-election-p02] The other 3 states where Debs finished 3rd were Oklahoma, where Roosevelt was not on the ballot; South Dakota, where Taft was not on the ballot; and California, where Taft was not on the ballot, but received write-in votes, causing Taft to finish 5th in California.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1912-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Debs was beaten by Chafin in two states, Vermont and Delaware, with Debs finishing 5th in both states.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1912-united-states-presidential-election-p02] The states where Chafin avoided finishing last were 19 of the 20 states where Reimer was on the ballot – Reimer finished last in all 20 states that he contested – as well as Vermont and Delaware, where Chafin managed to force Debs into last place.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1912-united-states-presidential-election-p02] The other state where Chafin avoided last place was California, where Taft was only a write-in candidate and finished last.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1912-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Reimer was not on the ballot in 28 states, while Chafin was not on the ballot in 8 states.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1912-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Only in Utah was Reimer on the ballot but Chafin was not.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1912-united-states-presidential-election-p02] The eleven states of the former Confederacy provided 5.44% of Taft's votes, with him taking 12.22% of the vote in that region while Roosevelt took 16.76%.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1912-united-states-presidential-election-p02] This was the last election where the winning presidential ticket featured two incumbent governors, with Wilson and his running mate Thomas R.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1912-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Marshall being the incumbent governors of New Jersey and Indiana, respectively.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1912-united-states-presidential-election-p02] In a plurality of 1,396 counties, no candidate obtained a majority.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1912-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Wilson won 1,969 counties but held a majority in only 1,237, less than Bryan had had in any of his campaigns.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1912-united-states-presidential-election-p02] "Other(s)", mostly Roosevelt, won a plurality in 772 counties and a majority in 305 counties.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1912-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Debs carried four counties: Lake and Beltrami in Minnesota, Burke in North Dakota, and Crawford in Kansas.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1912-united-states-presidential-election-p02] These are the only counties ever to vote for the Socialist presidential nominee.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1912-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Taft won a plurality in only 232 counties and a majority in only 35.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1912-united-states-presidential-election-p02] In addition to South Dakota and California, where there was no Taft ticket, Taft carried no counties in Maine, New Jersey, Minnesota, Nevada, Arizona, and seven "Solid South" states.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1912-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Nine counties did not record any votes due to either black disenfranchisement or being inhabited only by Native Americans, who would not gain full citizenship for 12 more years.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1912-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Results of various cities within the top 100 municipalities by the 1910 United States census.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1920-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Presidential elections were held in the United States on November 2, 1920.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1920-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The Republican ticket of senator Warren G.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1920-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Harding of Ohio and governor Calvin Coolidge of Massachusetts defeated the Democratic ticket of governor James M.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1920-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Cox of Ohio and assistant secretary Franklin D.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1920-united-states-presidential-election-p01] It was the first election held after the end of the First World War, and the first election after the ratification of the Nineteenth Amendment gave nationwide suffrage to women.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1920-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Incumbent president Woodrow Wilson, a Democrat who had served since 1913, privately hoped for a third term despite severe physical and mental disabilities from a stroke, but he had very little support.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1920-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Former president Theodore Roosevelt had been the frontrunner for the Republican nomination, but he died in 1919 without leaving an obvious heir to his progressive legacy.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1920-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The major parties turned to little-known dark horse candidates from the state of Ohio, a populous swing state with many electoral votes.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1920-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Cox won on the 44th ballot at the 1920 Democratic National Convention, defeating William Gibbs McAdoo (Wilson's son-in-law), A.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1920-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Mitchell Palmer, and several other candidates.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1920-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Harding emerged as a compromise candidate between the conservative and progressive wings of the Republican party, and he clinched his nomination on the tenth ballot at the 1920 Republican National Convention.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1920-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The election was dominated by the American social and political environment in the aftermath of World War I, which was marked by a hostile response to certain aspects of Wilson's foreign policy and a massive reaction against the reformist zeal of the Progressive Era.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1920-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The wartime economic boom had collapsed and the country was deep in a recession.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1920-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Wilson's advocacy for America's entry into the League of Nations, in the face of a return to non-interventionist opinion, challenged his effectiveness as president, and there were wars and revolutions overseas.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1920-united-states-presidential-election-p01] At home, the year 1919 was marked by major strikes in the meatpacking and steel industries and large-scale race riots in Chicago and other cities.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1920-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Additionally, the September 16, 1920, Wall Street bombing aroused fears of radicals and terrorists.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1920-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The Irish Catholic and German communities were outraged at Wilson's perceived support of their traditional enemy, Great Britain.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1920-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Harding all but ignored Cox in the race, and essentially campaigned against Wilson by calling for a "return to normalcy".
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1920-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Harding won a landslide victory, sweeping every state outside of the South and becoming the first Republican since the end of Reconstruction to win a former state of the Confederacy: Tennessee.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1920-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Harding's victory margin of 26.2 percent in the popular vote remains the largest popular-vote percentage margin ever since widespread popular elections began in the 1820s.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1920-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Cox won just 34.1 percent of the popular vote, and Socialist Eugene V.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1920-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Debs won 3.4 percent, despite being in prison at the time.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1920-united-states-presidential-election-p01] It was the first election in which women had the right to vote in all 48 states, which caused the total popular vote to increase dramatically, from 18.5 million in 1916 to 26.8 million in 1920.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1920-united-states-presidential-election-p01] It was the third presidential election in which both major party candidates were registered in the same home state (the others have been in 1860, 1904, 1940, 1944, and 2016).
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1920-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Coincidentally, the election was held on Harding's 55th birthday.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1920-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Both major-party vice-presidential nominees would later succeed to the presidency: Calvin Coolidge (Republican) upon Harding's death in 1923 and Franklin D.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1920-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Roosevelt (Democratic) after defeating Republican president Herbert Hoover in 1932.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1920-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Following the return of former president Theodore Roosevelt to the Republican Party after the previous election, speculation quickly grew as to whether he would make another run for the presidency.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1920-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Roosevelt's health declined seriously in 1918, however, and he died on January 6, 1919.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1920-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Attention then turned to the party's unsuccessful 1916 candidate, Charles Evans Hughes, who had run Wilson close that year, but Hughes remained aloof as to the prospect of another run, and ultimately ruled himself out following the death of his daughter early in 1920.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1920-united-states-presidential-election-p01] On June 8, the Republican National Convention met in Chicago.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1920-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The race was wide open, and soon the convention deadlocked between Major General Leonard Wood and Governor Frank Orren Lowden of Illinois.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1920-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Other names placed in nomination included Senators Warren G.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1920-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Harding from Ohio, Hiram Johnson from California, and Miles Poindexter from Washington, Governor Calvin Coolidge of Massachusetts, philanthropist Herbert Hoover from California, and Columbia University President Nicholas M.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1920-united-states-presidential-election-p01] La Follette from Wisconsin was not formally placed in nomination, but received the votes of his state delegation nonetheless.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1920-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Harding was nominated for president on the tenth ballot, after some delegates shifted their allegiances.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1920-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Harding's nomination, said to have been secured in negotiations among party bosses in a "smoke-filled room," was engineered by Harry M.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1920-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Daugherty, Harding's political manager, who became United States Attorney General after his election.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1920-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Parris argue that Daugherty's prediction has been given too much weight in narratives of the convention.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1920-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Once the presidential nomination was finally settled, the party bosses and Sen.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1920-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Irvine Lenroot to the delegates for the second spot, but the delegates revolted and nominated Coolidge, who was very popular over his handling of the Boston Police Strike from the year before.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1920-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Source for convention coverage: Richard C.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1920-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Parris, *Convention Decisions and Voting Records* (Washington DC: Brookings Institution, 1973), pp.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1920-united-states-presidential-election-p01] It was widely accepted prior to the election that President Woodrow Wilson would not run for a third term, and certainly would not be nominated if he did so.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1920-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Marshall long had desired to succeed Wilson, his indecisive handling of the situation around Wilson's illness and incapacity destroyed any credibility he had as a candidate, and in the end he did not formally put himself forward for the nomination.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1920-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The Democrats, meeting in San Francisco between June 28 and July 6 (the first time a major party held its nominating convention in an urban center on the Pacific coast), nominated another newspaper editor from Ohio, Governor James M.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1920-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Cox, as their presidential candidate, and 38-year-old Assistant Secretary of the Navy Franklin D.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1920-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Roosevelt, a fifth cousin and nephew by marriage of the late president Theodore Roosevelt, for vice-president.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1920-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Early favorites for the nomination had included McAdoo and Attorney General Alexander Mitchell Palmer.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1920-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Others placed in nomination included New York governor Al Smith, United Kingdom ambassador John W.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1920-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Edwards, and Oklahoma senator Robert Latham Owen.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1920-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Debs was incarcerated at the Atlanta federal penitentiary at the time for advocating non-compliance with the draft during World War I.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1920-united-states-presidential-election-p01] He received the largest number of popular votes ever received by a Socialist Party candidate in the United States, although not the largest percentage of the popular vote.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1920-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Debs received double this percentage in 1912.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1920-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The 1920 election was Debs's fifth and last attempt to become president.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1920-united-states-presidential-election-p01] In 1919, members of the Socialist Party who had come from Russian language federation of the party and other more radical groups within the party started to create their own papers and membership dues and cards.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1920-united-states-presidential-election-p01] These members supported a platform that was similar to the Communist International and elected twelve of their members to the fifteen-member National Executive Committee.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1920-united-states-presidential-election-p01] However, there was accusations of election irregularities and an Emergency Convention held on August 30, 1919, suspended seven of the party's twelve language federations and expelled the party affiliates in Michigan, Massachusetts, and Ohio.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1920-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The more radical members of the party held a convention in New York City in June 1919, which was attended by 94 delegates from twenty states.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1920-united-states-presidential-election-p01] A vote to create a new party was defeated by a vote of 55 to 38, causing 31 delegates to withdraw from the convention.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1920-united-states-presidential-election-p01] These 31 delegates held their own convention in Chicago on September 1, where they founded the Communist Party USA.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1920-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The Communist Party USA attempted to give its presidential nomination to Debs, but he declined the nomination.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1920-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The Socialist Party held its 1919 convention in Chicago with 140 delegates in attendance.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1920-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Twenty-six delegates, who were members of the party's left wing, left the convention.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1920-united-states-presidential-election-p01] These delegates attempted to unite with the Communist Party USA, but formed the Communist Labor Party of America on September 2, after those attempts failed.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1920-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The Socialist Party had 100,000 members before the splits, but it fell to 55,000 members while the Communist Party had 35,000 members and the Communist Labor Party had 10,000 members.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1920-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The Communist Party claimed to have 60,000 members while the Communist Labor Party claimed to have 30,000 members.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1920-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The United Communist Party was formed in May 1920 between the Communist Labor Party and some members of the Communist Party.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1920-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The United Communist Party and the Communist Party united in December 1921 to form the Workers Party of America.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1920-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Edward Henry, who was a friend of Debs, Lena Morrow Lewis, and Oscar Ameringer, nominated Debs for the party's nomination on May 13, 1920, and the 134 delegates to the national convention voted unanimously to give him the nomination.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1920-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Kate Richards O'Hare, who was also in prison, was considered for the vice-presidential nomination, but Seymour Stedman was selected by a vote of 106 to 26, which was later made unanimous, to have one of the candidates campaign.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1920-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Maurer was also considered for the vice-presidential nomination, but he declined due to his duties as head of the Pennsylvania Federation of Labor.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1920-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Debs accepted the presidential nomination in an Atlanta prison on May 29, after being notified by Seymour, James Oneal, and Julius Gerber.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1920-united-states-presidential-election-p01] During the campaign the Socialists had four airplanes drop socialist literature over Toledo, Ohio.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1920-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The wife of Charles Edward Russell claimed that the ghost of Susan B.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1920-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Over 60,000 people donated to the Socialist Party's campaign fund.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1920-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Gerber predicted that Debs would receive three million votes and that five Socialists would be elected to Congress.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1920-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Debs received 913,693 votes with his largest amount of support coming from New York.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1920-united-states-presidential-election-p01] His vote total was over 50 percent more than what Allan L.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1920-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Benson had received in the 1916 election.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1920-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Debs later chose to not run for president in the 1924 election and instead supported Robert M.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1920-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The ticket favored by most present was that of William Jennings Bryan for president and William "Billy" Sunday for vice president, and indeed when a motion was made to nominate Bryan by acclamation, of the more than two hundred present it was only opposed by six.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1920-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Upon hearing of his nomination, however, Bryan declined the gesture, not wishing to remain singularly focused on the prohibition question or to sever his ties with the Democratic Party entirely.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1920-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Some had considered Billy Sunday a possible substitute but Sunday was "satisfied" with Republican nominee Warren Harding, while others thought about potentially nominating Henry Ford as their standard-bearer.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1920-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Historian David Leigh Colvin of New York was nominated for the vice presidency.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1920-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Ferguson, a former governor of Texas, announced his candidacy on April 21, 1920, in Temple, Texas, under the badge of "American Party".
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1920-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Ferguson was opposed to Democrats whom he saw as too controlled by elite academic interests as seen when Woodrow Wilson endorsed rival Thomas H.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1920-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Ball in the gubernatorial primary, and hoped to help the Republicans carry Texas for the first time (Texas never went Republican during Reconstruction).
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1920-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Initially Ferguson and running mate William J.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1920-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Hough hoped to carry their campaign to other states, but Ferguson was unable to get on the ballot anywhere outside of Texas.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1920-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Ferguson did manage to gain almost 10 percent of the vote in Texas, and won eleven counties in the southeast of the state.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1920-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Warren Harding spoke of "return to normalcy", playing upon the weariness of the American public after the social upheaval of the Progressive Era, World War I, and the Spanish flu.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1920-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Additionally, the international responsibilities engendered by the Allied victory in World War I and the Treaty of Versailles proved deeply unpopular, causing a reaction against Wilson, who had pushed especially hard for the latter.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1920-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Irish Americans were powerful in the Democratic party, and groups such as Clan na Gael opposed going to war alongside their enemy Britain, especially after the violent suppression of the Easter Rising of 1916.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1920-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Wilson won them over in 1917 by promising to ask Britain to give Ireland its independence.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1920-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Wilson had won the presidential election of 1916 with strong support from German Americans and Irish Americans, largely because of his slogan "He kept us out of war" and the longstanding American policy of isolationism.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1920-united-states-presidential-election-p01] At the Paris Peace Conference in 1919, however, he reneged on his commitments to the Irish-American community, who vehemently denounced him.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1920-united-states-presidential-election-p01] His dilemma was that Britain was his war ally.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1920-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Events such as the anti-British Black Tom and Kingsland explosions in 1916 on American soil (in part the result of wartime Irish and German co-ordination) and the Irish anti-conscription crisis of 1918 were all embarrassing to recall in 1920.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1920-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Britain had already passed an Irish Home Rule Act in 1914, suspended for the war's duration.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1920-united-states-presidential-election-p01] However the 1916 Easter Rising in Dublin had led to increased support for the more radical Sinn Féin who in 1919 formed the First Dáil, effectively declaring Ireland independent, sparking the Irish War of Independence.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1920-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Britain would pass the Government of Ireland Act in late 1920, by which Ireland would have two home-ruled states within the British empire.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1920-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The provisions of these were inadequate to the supporters of the Irish Republic, however, which claimed full sovereignty.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1920-united-states-presidential-election-p01] This position was also supported by many Irish Americans.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1920-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The American Committee for Relief in Ireland was set up in 1920 to assist victims of the Irish War of Independence of 1919–21.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1920-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Some Irish-American senators joined the "irreconcilables" who blocked the ratification of the Treaty of Versailles and United States membership in the League of Nations.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1920-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Of the $5,500,000 raised by supporters of the Irish Republic in the United States in 1919–20, the Dublin parliament (Dáil Éireann) voted in June 1920 to spend $500,000 on the American presidential election.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1920-united-states-presidential-election-p01] How this money was spent remains unclear.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1920-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Ironically, the lawyer who had advised the fundraisers was Franklin D.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1920-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Roosevelt, the losing vice-presidential candidate.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1920-united-states-presidential-election-p01] In any case, the Irish American city machines sat on their hands during the election, allowing the Republicans to roll up unprecedented landslides in every major city.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1920-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Many German-American Democrats voted Republican or stayed home, giving the GOP landslides in the rural Midwest.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1920-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Wilson had hoped for a "solemn referendum" on the League of Nations, but did not get one.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1920-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Harding waffled on the League, thereby keeping Idaho senator William Borah and other Republican "irreconcilables" in line.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1920-united-states-presidential-election-p01] As reporter Brand Whitlock observed, the League was a much more important issue in government circles than to the electorate.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1920-united-states-presidential-election-p01] He also noted that the campaign was not waged on issues: "The people, indeed, do not know what ideas Harding or Cox represents; neither do Harding or Cox.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1920-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Great is democracy." False rumors circulated that Senator Harding had "Negro blood," but this did not greatly hurt Harding's election campaign.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1920-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Governor Cox made a whirlwind campaign that took him to rallies, train station speeches, and formal addresses, reaching audiences totaling perhaps two million, whereas Senator Harding relied upon a "Front Porch Campaign" like that of William McKinley in 1896.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1920-united-states-presidential-election-p01] It brought thousands of voters to Marion, Ohio, where Harding spoke from his home.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1920-united-states-presidential-election-p01] GOP campaign manager Will Hays spent some $8.1 million, nearly four times the money Cox's campaign spent.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1920-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Hays used national advertising in a major way (with advice from adman Albert Lasker).
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1920-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The theme was Harding's own slogan "America First".
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1920-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Harding's landslide came from all directions except the South.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1920-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Irish- and German-American voters who had backed Wilson and peace in 1916 now voted against Wilson and Versailles.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1920-united-states-presidential-election-p01] "A vote for Harding", said the German-language press, "is a vote against the persecutions suffered by German-Americans during the war".
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1920-united-states-presidential-election-p01] No major German-language newspaper supported Governor Cox.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1920-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Many Irish Americans, bitterly angry at Wilson's refusal to help Ireland at Versailles, simply abstained from voting in the presidential election.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1920-united-states-presidential-election-p01] This allowed the Republicans to mobilize the ethnic vote, and Harding swept the big cities.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1920-united-states-presidential-election-p01] This was the first election in which women from every state were allowed to vote, following the passage of the 19th Amendment to the Constitution in August 1920 (just in time for the general election).
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1920-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Harding marked the first time since the end of Reconstruction that even one of the eleven states of the former Confederacy had voted for a Republican presidential candidate.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1920-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The last Republican to claim Tennessee had been Ulysses S.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1920-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Despite the magnitude of Cox's defeat, his running mate Franklin D.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1920-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Roosevelt became a well-known political figure because of his active and energetic campaign (despite suffering an illness in August 1921 that left him paralyzed from the waist down).
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1920-united-states-presidential-election-p01] In 1928, he was elected Governor of New York, and in 1932 he was elected president.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1920-united-states-presidential-election-p01] He remained in power until his death in 1945 as the longest-serving American president in history.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1920-united-states-presidential-election-p02] The total vote for 1920 was roughly 26,750,000, an increase of eight million from 1916.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1920-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Harding won in all twelve cities with populations above 500,000.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1920-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Harding won a net vote total of 1,540,000 from the twelve largest cities, the most for any Republican and fifth highest for any candidate from 1920 to 1948.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1920-united-states-presidential-election-p02] The Democratic vote was almost exactly the vote from 1916, but the Republican vote nearly doubled, as did the "other" vote.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1920-united-states-presidential-election-p02] As noted earlier, the great increase in the total number of votes is mainly attributable to the passage of the Nineteenth Amendment to the United States Constitution, which gave women the right to vote.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1920-united-states-presidential-election-p02] However, Georgia and Mississippi refused to let any women vote in this election, claiming that the amendment's August ratification had given women insufficient time to complete their voter registration.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1920-united-states-presidential-election-p02] The Republican ticket carried nearly two-thirds of the counties (1,949).
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1920-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Democrats carried only 1,101 counties, fewer than Alton Parker had carried in 1904 and consequently the fewest during the Fourth Party System until that point (Al Smith would carry even fewer in 1928).
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1920-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Harding carried every county in the Pacific section, where Wilson had carried 76 in 1916.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1920-united-states-presidential-election-p02] In the Mountain section Cox carried only thirteen counties, seven of them in New Mexico bordering Texas, whereas Wilson carried all but twenty-one Mountain Section counties in 1916.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1920-united-states-presidential-election-p02] At least one county was lost in every section in the Union and in every state except South Carolina and Mississippi.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1920-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Eleven counties in Texas recorded a plurality for Ferguson.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1920-united-states-presidential-election-p02] With the tipping point state of Rhode Island being decided by a 31.2 percent margin, the 1920 election has the largest margin of victory in the tipping point state in American history.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1920-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Wilson had won the support of Americans of German, Italian, Irish, or Jewish descent in the 1916 election, but Cox lost in all of those demographics and received less support from Jewish voters than Debs.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1920-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Harding received support from over 90 percent of black voters.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1920-united-states-presidential-election-p02] The distribution of the county vote accurately represents the overwhelming character of the majority vote.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1920-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Harding received 60.35 percent of the total vote, the largest percentage in the Fourth Party System, exceeding Franklin D.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1920-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Although the Democratic share was 34.13 percent, in no section did its voting share sink below 24 percent, and in three sections, the Democrats topped the poll.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1920-united-states-presidential-election-p02] The Democratic Party was still a significant opposition on national terms, even though Cox won only eleven states and had fewer votes in the Electoral College than Parker had won in 1904.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1920-united-states-presidential-election-p02] More than two-thirds of the Cox vote was in states carried by Harding.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1920-united-states-presidential-election-p02] The distribution of the vote by counties, and the study of percentages in sections, states, and counties, seem to show that it was Wilson and foreign policies that received the brunt of attack, not the Democratic Party and the domestic proposals of the period 1896–1914.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1920-united-states-presidential-election-p02] This is one of three elections since the Civil War (along with those of 1924 and 1996) in which national voter turnout was below 50 percent.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1920-united-states-presidential-election-p02] This was also the third presidential election in which both major party candidates were registered in the same home state; the others have been in 1860, 1904, 1940, 1944, and 2016.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1920-united-states-presidential-election-p02] The eleven states of the former Confederacy provided 5.83% of Harding's votes, with him taking 35.09% of the vote in that region.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1920-united-states-presidential-election-p02] For the 1916 election, only a single radio station, 2XG, an experimental station operated by the De Forest Radio Telephone and Telegraph Company in New York City, made an audio broadcast of the election returns.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1920-united-states-presidential-election-p02] For 1920, this increased to at least four stations, including the *Detroit News*' "Detroit News Radiophone" station, 8MK (later WWJ); a temporary arrangement made by the *Saint Louis Post-Dispatch* in conjunction with William E.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1920-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Woods of the Benwoods Company, and the *Buffalo Evening News*, over an amateur station operated by Charles C.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1920-united-states-presidential-election-p02] However, the most prominent station was the debut of Westinghouse's ambitious commercial broadcast service, as announcers at 8ZZ (later KDKA) in East Pittsburgh read telegraph ticker results as they came in.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1920-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Later station publicity proclaimed that this broadcast "was a national sensation, acclaimed by newspapers all over the country".
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1920-united-states-presidential-election-p02] However a comprehensive review of contemporary newspapers determined that reports, although positive, actually appeared only in a few local papers, thus it "was not an immediate 'sensation' and that the fame of this event developed over time with later celebratory accounts".
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1940-united-states-presidential-election] Presidential elections were held in the United States on November 5, 1940.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1940-united-states-presidential-election] The Democratic ticket of incumbent President Franklin D.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1940-united-states-presidential-election] Roosevelt and Secretary of Agriculture Henry Wallace defeated the Republican ticket of businessman Wendell Willkie and senator Charles McNary to be re-elected for an unprecedented third term in office.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1940-united-states-presidential-election] Until 1988, this was the last time in which the incumbent's party won three consecutive presidential elections.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1940-united-states-presidential-election] It was also the fourth presidential election in which both major party candidates were registered in the same home state; the others have been in 1860, 1904, 1920, 1944, and 2016.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1940-united-states-presidential-election] The election was contested in the shadow of World War II in Europe, as the United States was finally emerging from the Great Depression.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1940-united-states-presidential-election] Roosevelt did not want to campaign for a third term initially, but was driven by worsening conditions in Europe.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1940-united-states-presidential-election] He and his allies sought to defuse challenges from other party leaders such as James Farley and Vice President John Nance Garner.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1940-united-states-presidential-election] The 1940 Democratic National Convention re-nominated Roosevelt on the first ballot, while Garner was replaced on the ticket by Secretary of Agriculture Henry A.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1940-united-states-presidential-election] Willkie, a dark horse candidate, unexpectedly defeated conservative Senator Robert A.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1940-united-states-presidential-election] Taft and Manhattan District Attorney Thomas E.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1940-united-states-presidential-election] Dewey on the sixth presidential ballot of the 1940 Republican National Convention.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1940-united-states-presidential-election] Roosevelt, acutely aware of strong isolationist and non-interventionist sentiment, promised there would be no involvement in foreign wars if he were reelected.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1940-united-states-presidential-election] Willkie, who had not previously run for public office, conducted an energetic campaign, managing to revive Republican strength in areas of the Midwest and Northeast.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1940-united-states-presidential-election] He criticized perceived incompetence and waste in the New Deal, warned of the dangers of breaking the two-term tradition, and accused Roosevelt of secretly planning to take the country into World War II.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1940-united-states-presidential-election] However, Willkie's association with big business damaged his cause, as many working class voters blamed corporations and business leaders for the Great Depression.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1940-united-states-presidential-election] Roosevelt led in all pre-election polls and won a comfortable victory; his margins, though still significant, were less decisive than they had been in 1932 and 1936.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1940-united-states-presidential-election] Throughout the winter, spring, and summer of 1940, there was much speculation as to whether Roosevelt would break with longstanding tradition and run for an unprecedented third term.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1940-united-states-presidential-election] The two-term tradition, although not yet enshrined in the Constitution, had been established by George Washington when he refused to run for a third term in 1796; other former presidents, such as Ulysses S.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1940-united-states-presidential-election] Grant in 1880 and Theodore Roosevelt in 1912 had made serious attempts to run for a third term, but the former failed to be nominated, while the latter, forced to run on a third-party ticket, lost to Woodrow Wilson due to the split in the Republican vote.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1940-united-states-presidential-election] President Roosevelt refused to state definitely whether he would run for a third term.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1940-united-states-presidential-election] He even indicated to some ambitious Democrats that he would not run.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1940-united-states-presidential-election] Two of them thus decided to seek the Democratic nomination.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1940-united-states-presidential-election] These were James Farley, his former campaign manager, and Vice President John Nance Garner.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1940-united-states-presidential-election] Garner was a Texas conservative who had come to disagree with Roosevelt's liberal economic and social policies, and declined to run for a third term as vice president.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1940-united-states-presidential-election] However, as Nazi Germany swept through western Europe and menaced the United Kingdom in the summer of 1940, Roosevelt decided that only he had the necessary experience and skills to see the nation safely through the Nazi threat.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1940-united-states-presidential-election] He was aided by the party's political bosses, who feared that no Democrat except Roosevelt could defeat the popular Willkie.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1940-united-states-presidential-election] At the July 1940 Democratic National Convention in Chicago, Roosevelt easily swept aside challenges from Farley and Garner.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1940-united-states-presidential-election] Roosevelt picked Secretary of Agriculture Henry A.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1940-united-states-presidential-election] Wallace of Iowa to replace Garner on the ticket.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1940-united-states-presidential-election] An outspoken liberal who had been a Republican until he joined Roosevelt's cabinet, he met strong opposition from conservatives and party traditionalists.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1940-united-states-presidential-election] Wallace was also known as "eccentric" in his private life: some years earlier, he had been a follower of Theosophist mystic Nicholas Roerich.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1940-united-states-presidential-election] But Roosevelt insisted that without Wallace he would not run.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1940-united-states-presidential-election] First Lady Eleanor Roosevelt came to Chicago to vouch for Wallace, and he won the vice-presidential nomination with 626 votes to 329 for House Speaker William B.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1940-united-states-presidential-election] The three leading candidates for the Republican nomination - Senator Robert A.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1940-united-states-presidential-election] Vandenberg from Michigan, and District Attorney Thomas E.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1940-united-states-presidential-election] Dewey from New York - were all isolationists to varying degrees.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1940-united-states-presidential-election] Taft was the leader of the conservative, isolationist wing of the Republican Party, and his main strength was in his native Midwestern United States and parts of the Southern United States.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1940-united-states-presidential-election] Dewey, the District Attorney for Manhattan, had risen to national fame as the "Gangbuster" prosecutor who had sent numerous infamous Mafia figures to prison, most notably Lucky Luciano, the organized-crime boss of New York City.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1940-united-states-presidential-election] Dewey had won most of the presidential primaries in the spring of 1940, and he came into the Republican Convention in June with the largest number of delegate votes, although he was still well below the number needed to win.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1940-united-states-presidential-election] Vandenberg, the senior Republican in the Senate, was the "favorite son" candidate of the Michigan delegation and was considered a possible compromise candidate if Taft or Dewey faltered.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1940-united-states-presidential-election] Former President Herbert Hoover was also spoken of as a compromise candidate.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1940-united-states-presidential-election] However, each of these candidates had weaknesses that could be exploited.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1940-united-states-presidential-election] Taft's outspoken isolationism and opposition to any American involvement in the European war convinced many Republican leaders that he could not win a general election, particularly as France fell to the Nazis in June 1940 and Germany threatened the United Kingdom.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1940-united-states-presidential-election] Dewey's relative youth—he was only 38 in 1940—and lack of any foreign-policy experience caused his candidacy to weaken as the Wehrmacht emerged as a fearsome threat.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1940-united-states-presidential-election] In 1940, Vandenberg was also an isolationist (he would change his foreign-policy stance during World War II) and his lackadaisical, lethargic campaign never caught the voters' attention.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1940-united-states-presidential-election] Hoover still bore the stigma of having presided over the Wall Street Crash of 1929 and the subsequent Great Depression.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1940-united-states-presidential-election] This left an opening for a dark horse candidate to emerge.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1940-united-states-presidential-election] A Wall Street-based industrialist named Wendell Willkie, who had never before run for public office, emerged as the unlikely nominee.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1940-united-states-presidential-election] Willkie, a native of Indiana and a former Democrat who had supported Franklin Roosevelt in the 1932 United States presidential election, was considered an improbable choice.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1940-united-states-presidential-election] Willkie had first come to public attention as an articulate critic of Roosevelt's attempt to break up electrical power monopolies.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1940-united-states-presidential-election] Willkie was the CEO of the Commonwealth & Southern Corporation, which provided electrical power to customers in eleven states.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1940-united-states-presidential-election] In 1933, President Roosevelt had created the Tennessee Valley Authority (TVA), which promised to provide flood control and cheap electricity to the impoverished people of the Tennessee Valley.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1940-united-states-presidential-election] However, the government-run TVA would compete with Willkie's Commonwealth & Southern, and this led Willkie to criticize and oppose the TVA's attempt to compete with private power companies.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1940-united-states-presidential-election] Willkie argued that the government had unfair advantages over private corporations, and should thus avoid competing directly against them.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1940-united-states-presidential-election] However, Willkie did not dismiss all of Roosevelt's social welfare programs, indeed supporting those he believed could not be managed any better by the free enterprise system.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1940-united-states-presidential-election] Furthermore, unlike the leading Republican candidates, Willkie was a forceful and outspoken advocate of aid to the Allies of World War II, especially the United Kingdom.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1940-united-states-presidential-election] His support of giving all aid to the British "short of declaring war" won him the support of many Republicans on the East Coast of the United States, who disagreed with their party's isolationist leaders in Congress.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1940-united-states-presidential-election] Willkie's persuasive arguments impressed these Republicans, who believed that he would be an attractive presidential candidate.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1940-united-states-presidential-election] Even so, Willkie remained a long-shot candidate; the May 8 Gallup Poll showed Dewey at 67% support among Republicans, followed by Vandenberg and Taft, with Willkie at only 3%.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1940-united-states-presidential-election] The German Army's rapid Blitzkrieg campaign into France in May 1940 shook American public opinion, even as Taft was telling a Kansas audience that America needed to concentrate on domestic issues to prevent Roosevelt from using the war crisis to extend socialism at home.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1940-united-states-presidential-election] Both Dewey and Vandenberg also continued to oppose any aid to the United Kingdom that might lead to war with Nazi Germany.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1940-united-states-presidential-election] Nevertheless, sympathy for the embattled British was mounting daily, and this aided Willkie's candidacy.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1940-united-states-presidential-election] By mid-June, little over one week before the Republican Convention opened, the Gallup poll reported that Willkie had moved into second place with 17%, and that Dewey was slipping.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1940-united-states-presidential-election] Fueled by his favorable media attention, Willkie's pro-British statements won over many of the delegates.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1940-united-states-presidential-election] As the delegates were arriving in Philadelphia, Gallup reported that Willkie had surged to 29%, Dewey had slipped five more points to 47%, and Taft, Vandenberg and Hoover trailed at 8%, 8%, and 6% respectively.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1940-united-states-presidential-election] Hundreds of thousands, perhaps as many as one million, telegrams urging support for Willkie poured in, many from "Willkie Clubs" that had sprung up across the country.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1940-united-states-presidential-election] Millions more signed petitions circulating everywhere.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1940-united-states-presidential-election] At the 1940 Republican National Convention itself, keynote speaker Harold Stassen, the Governor of Minnesota, announced his support for Willkie and became his official floor manager.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1940-united-states-presidential-election] Hundreds of vocal Willkie supporters packed the upper galleries of the convention hall.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1940-united-states-presidential-election] Willkie's amateur status and fresh face appealed to delegates as well as voters.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1940-united-states-presidential-election] Most of the delegations were selected not by primaries, but by party leaders in each state, and they had a keen sense of the fast-changing pulse of public opinion.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1940-united-states-presidential-election] Gallup found the same thing in polling data not reported until after the convention: Willkie had moved ahead among Republican voters by 44% to only 29% for the collapsing Dewey.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1940-united-states-presidential-election] As the pro-Willkie galleries chanted "We Want Willkie!" the delegates on the convention floor began their vote.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1940-united-states-presidential-election] Dewey led on the first ballot, but steadily lost strength thereafter.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1940-united-states-presidential-election] Both Taft and Willkie gained in strength on each ballot, and by the fourth ballot it was obvious that either Willkie or Taft would be the nominee.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1940-united-states-presidential-election] The key moments came when the delegations of large states such as Michigan, Pennsylvania, and New York left Dewey and Vandenberg and switched to Willkie, giving him the victory on the sixth ballot.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1940-united-states-presidential-election] Willkie's nomination was one of the most dramatic moments in any political convention.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1940-united-states-presidential-election] Having given little thought to whom he would select as his vice-presidential nominee, Willkie left the decision to convention chairman and Massachusetts Representative Joseph Martin, the House Minority Leader, who suggested Senate Minority Leader Charles L.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1940-united-states-presidential-election] Despite the fact that McNary had spearheaded a "Stop Willkie" campaign late in the balloting, the convention picked him to be Willkie's running mate.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1940-united-states-presidential-election] The Gallup Poll accurately predicted the election outcome.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1940-united-states-presidential-election] However, the American Institute of Public Opinion, responsible for the Gallup Poll, avoided predicting the outcome, citing a four percent margin of error.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1940-united-states-presidential-election] The Gallup Poll also found that, if there was no war in Europe, voters preferred Willkie over Roosevelt.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1940-united-states-presidential-election] Willkie also criticized what he claimed was the incompetence and waste in Roosevelt's New Deal welfare programs.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1940-united-states-presidential-election] He stated that as president he would keep most of Roosevelt's government programs, but would make them more efficient.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1940-united-states-presidential-election] However, many Americans still blamed business leaders for the Great Depression, and the fact that Willkie symbolized "Big Business" hurt him with many working-class voters.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1940-united-states-presidential-election] Willkie was a fearless campaigner; he often visited industrial areas where Republicans were still blamed for causing the Great Depression and where Roosevelt was highly popular.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1940-united-states-presidential-election] In these areas, Willkie frequently had rotten fruit and vegetables thrown at him and was heckled by crowds; still, he was unfazed.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1940-united-states-presidential-election] Willkie also accused Roosevelt of leaving the nation unprepared for war, but Roosevelt's military buildup and transformation of the nation into the "Arsenal of Democracy" removed the "unpreparedness" charge as a major issue.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1940-united-states-presidential-election] Willkie then reversed his approach and charged Roosevelt with secretly planning to take the nation into World War II.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1940-united-states-presidential-election] This accusation did cut into Roosevelt's support.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1940-united-states-presidential-election] In response, Roosevelt, in a pledge that he would later regret, promised that he would "not send American boys into any foreign wars." The United Kingdom and Germany actively interfered throughout the election, hoping to exploit public sentiments and cultivate political contacts.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1940-united-states-presidential-election] Roosevelt led in all pre-election opinion polls by various margins.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1940-united-states-presidential-election] On Election Day—November 5, 1940, he received 27.3 million votes to Willkie's 22.3 million, and in the Electoral College, he defeated Willkie by a margin of 449 to 82.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1940-united-states-presidential-election] Willkie did get over six million more votes than the Republican nominee in 1936, Alf Landon, and he ran strong in rural areas in the American Midwest, taking over 57% of the farm vote.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1940-united-states-presidential-election] Many counties in the Midwest have not voted for a Democrat since.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1940-united-states-presidential-election] Roosevelt, meanwhile, carried every American city with a population of more than 400,000 except Cincinnati, Ohio.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1940-united-states-presidential-election] Of the 106 cities with more than 100,000 population, he won 61% of the votes cast; in the Southern United States as a whole, he won 73% of the total vote.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1940-united-states-presidential-election] In the remainder of the country (the rural and small-town Northern United States), Willkie had a majority of 53%.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1940-united-states-presidential-election] In the cities, there was a class differential, with the white-collar and middle-class voters supporting the Republican candidate, and working class, blue-collar voters going for FDR.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1940-united-states-presidential-election] In the North, Roosevelt won 87% of the Jewish vote, 73% of the Catholics, and 61% of the nonmembers, while all the major Protestant denominations showed majorities for Willkie.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1940-united-states-presidential-election] Roosevelt's net vote totals in the twelve largest cities decreased from 3,479,000 votes in the 1936 election to 2,112,000 votes, but it was still higher than his result from the 1932 election when he won by 1,791,000 votes.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1940-united-states-presidential-election] Roosevelt was the third of just four presidents in United States history to win re-election with a lower percentage of the electoral vote than in their prior elections, the other three were James Madison in 1812, Woodrow Wilson in 1916 and Barack Obama in 2012.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1940-united-states-presidential-election] Additionally, Roosevelt was the fourth of only five presidents to win re-election with a smaller percentage of the popular vote than in prior elections, the other four are Madison in 1812, Andrew Jackson in 1832, Grover Cleveland in 1892, and Obama in 2012.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1940-united-states-presidential-election] This marked the first time since 1892 that the Democrats won the popular vote in three consecutive elections, and the first since 1836 where they won three consecutive elections.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1940-united-states-presidential-election] Although at a rate lower than 1936, Roosevelt maintained his strong majorities from labor unions, big city political machines, ethnic minority voters, and the traditionally Democratic Solid South.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1940-united-states-presidential-election] Roosevelt's third consecutive victory inspired the Twenty-second Amendment, limiting the number of terms a person may be president.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1940-united-states-presidential-election] As of 2024, Roosevelt was the sixth of eight presidential nominees to win a significant number of electoral votes in at least three elections, the others being Thomas Jefferson, Henry Clay, Andrew Jackson, Grover Cleveland, William Jennings Bryan, Richard Nixon, and Donald Trump.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1940-united-states-presidential-election] Of these, Jackson, Cleveland, and Roosevelt also won the popular vote in at least three elections.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1940-united-states-presidential-election] Jefferson, Cleveland, Roosevelt, and Trump were also their respective party's nominees for three consecutive elections.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1940-united-states-presidential-election] This was the first time in which North Dakota voted for a losing candidate and the first time since 1892 in which a Democrat won without Colorado, Kansas, and Nebraska.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1940-united-states-presidential-election] This was also the first time anyone won without Colorado and Nebraska since 1908, and Kansas since 1900.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1940-united-states-presidential-election] Willkie and McNary both died in 1944 (October 8 and February 25, respectively), which is the first, and to date only time both members of a major-party presidential ticket died during the term for which they sought election.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1940-united-states-presidential-election] Had they been elected, Willkie's death would have resulted in the Secretary of State becoming acting president for the remainder of the term ending on January 20, 1945, in accordance with the Presidential Succession Act of 1886.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1940-united-states-presidential-election] The eleven states of the former Confederacy provided 4.53% of Willkie's votes, with him taking 21.65% of the vote in that region.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1940-united-states-presidential-election] The British government engaged covert intelligence operations to support Roosevelt, including the planting of false news stories, wiretaps, "October surprises", and other intelligence activities.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1940-united-states-presidential-election] The German government had allocated $5 million as a campaign war chest via the German embassy to bribe Democratic delegates at the 1940 convention, using American businessman William Rhodes Davis as a conduit.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1940-united-states-presidential-election] Davis was sympathetic to the German cause after his meeting with Hermann Göring and was enlisted for this purpose.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1940-united-states-presidential-election] Later, he directed some of these funds towards supporting anti-Roosevelt radio broadcasts by the isolationist labor leader John L.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1940-united-states-presidential-election] Lewis, with the aim of impeding Roosevelt's re-election bid.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1940-united-states-presidential-election] Initially a supporter of Roosevelt in 1936, Davis had become disillusioned by 1940, and the two had grown apart over foreign policy.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1940-united-states-presidential-election] The German envoy in Mexico had also requested $160,000 to sway an unnamed Democratic Party operative in Pennsylvania to unseat interventionist Democratic Senator Joseph Guffey, who was a prominent critic of Nazi Germany.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1940-united-states-presidential-election] Davis was later identified as Abwehr agent C-80 following his death in August 1941.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1944-united-states-presidential-election] Presidential elections were held on Tuesday, November 7, 1944.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1944-united-states-presidential-election] The election took place during World War II which ended the following year.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1944-united-states-presidential-election] Roosevelt and Senator Harry Truman defeated the Republican ticket of New York Governor Thomas E.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1944-united-states-presidential-election] Dewey and Ohio Governor John Bricker to win an unprecedented fourth term.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1944-united-states-presidential-election] It was also the fifth presidential election in which both major party candidates were registered in the same home state; the others have been in 1860, 1904, 1920, 1940, and 2016.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1944-united-states-presidential-election] Though the margin of victory was still a landslide, this was Roosevelt's weakest performance in his four elections, and the popular vote split was less lopsided.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1944-united-states-presidential-election] Roosevelt had become the first president to win a third term with his victory in the 1940 presidential election, with little doubt that he would seek a fourth term.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1944-united-states-presidential-election] Unlike in 1940, Roosevelt faced little opposition within his own party, and he easily won the presidential nomination of the 1944 Democratic National Convention.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1944-united-states-presidential-election] Concerned that Roosevelt's ill health would mean the vice president would likely become president, the convention dropped Roosevelt's vice president Henry A.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1944-united-states-presidential-election] Wallace in favor of the lesser known Senator Harry S.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1944-united-states-presidential-election] Governor Dewey of New York emerged as the front-runner for the Republican nomination after his victory in the Wisconsin primary, and he defeated conservative Governor John W.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1944-united-states-presidential-election] Bricker at the 1944 Republican National Convention.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1944-united-states-presidential-election] As World War II was going well for the United States and the Allies, Roosevelt remained popular despite his long tenure.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1944-united-states-presidential-election] Dewey campaigned against the New Deal and for a smaller government, but was ultimately unsuccessful in convincing the country to change course.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1944-united-states-presidential-election] The election was closer than Roosevelt's other presidential campaigns, but Roosevelt still won by a 7.5 percentage point margin in the popular vote and by a wide margin in the Electoral College.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1944-united-states-presidential-election] Rumors of Roosevelt's ill health, although somewhat dispelled by his vigorous campaigning, proved to be true; Roosevelt died less than three months into his fourth term and was succeeded by Truman.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1944-united-states-presidential-election] Roosevelt would be the last major party candidate to have been nominated by their party for three or more consecutive elections until Donald Trump in 2024.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1944-united-states-presidential-election] President Roosevelt was the popular, wartime incumbent and faced little formal opposition.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1944-united-states-presidential-election] Although many Southern Democrats mistrusted Roosevelt's racial policies, he brought enormous war activities to the region and the end of its marginal status was in sight.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1944-united-states-presidential-election] No major figure opposed Roosevelt publicly, and he was re-nominated easily when the Democratic Convention met in Chicago.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1944-united-states-presidential-election] Some pro-segregationist delegates tried to unite behind Virginia senator Harry F.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1944-united-states-presidential-election] Byrd, but he refused to campaign actively against Roosevelt, and did not get enough delegates to seriously threaten the President's chances.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1944-united-states-presidential-election] The obvious physical decline in the president's appearance, as well as rumors of secret health problems, led many delegates and party leaders to strongly oppose Vice President Henry A.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1944-united-states-presidential-election] Opposition to Wallace came especially from Catholic leaders in big cities and moderate Democrats.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1944-united-states-presidential-election] Wallace, who had been Roosevelt's vice president since January 1941, was regarded by most conservatives as being too left-wing and personally eccentric to be next in line for the presidency.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1944-united-states-presidential-election] He had performed so poorly as economic coordinator that Roosevelt had to remove him from that post.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1944-united-states-presidential-election] Numerous moderate party leaders privately sent word to Roosevelt that they would fight Wallace's re-nomination as vice president and proposed instead Senator Harry S.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1944-united-states-presidential-election] Truman was highly visible as the chairman of a Senate wartime committee investigating fraud and inefficiency in the war program.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1944-united-states-presidential-election] Roosevelt, who personally liked Wallace and knew little about Truman, agreed reluctantly to accept Truman as his running mate to preserve party unity.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1944-united-states-presidential-election] Even so, many delegates on the left refused to abandon Wallace, and they voted for him on the first ballot.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1944-united-states-presidential-election] However, enough large Northern, Midwestern, and Southern states supported Truman to give him victory on the second ballot.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1944-united-states-presidential-election] The fight over the vice-presidential nomination proved to be consequential; the ticket won and Roosevelt died in April 1945, and Truman instead of Wallace became the nation's thirty-third President.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1944-united-states-presidential-election] As 1944 began, the frontrunners for the Republican nomination appeared to be Wendell Willkie, the party's 1940 dark horse nominee, Senator Robert A.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1944-united-states-presidential-election] Taft from Ohio, the leader of the party's conservatives, New York Governor Thomas E.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1944-united-states-presidential-election] Dewey, the leader of the party's moderate eastern establishment, General Douglas MacArthur, then serving as an Allied commander in the Pacific theater of the war, and former Minnesota Governor Harold Stassen, then serving as a U.S. naval officer in the Pacific.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1944-united-states-presidential-election] Taft surprised many by declining to run for president as he wanted to remain in the Senate; instead, he voiced his support for a fellow Ohio conservative, Governor John W.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1944-united-states-presidential-election] With Taft out of the race some Republican conservatives favored General MacArthur.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1944-united-states-presidential-election] However, MacArthur's chances were limited by the fact that he was leading Allied forces against Japan, and thus could not campaign for the nomination.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1944-united-states-presidential-election] His supporters entered his name in the Wisconsin primary nonetheless.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1944-united-states-presidential-election] The Wisconsin primary proved to be the key contest, as Dewey won by a surprisingly wide margin.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1944-united-states-presidential-election] He took fourteen delegates to four for Harold Stassen, while MacArthur won the three remaining delegates.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1944-united-states-presidential-election] Willkie was shut out in the Wisconsin primary; he did not win a single delegate.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1944-united-states-presidential-election] His unexpectedly poor showing in Wisconsin forced him to withdraw as a candidate for the nomination.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1944-united-states-presidential-election] However, at the time of his sudden death in early October 1944, Willkie had endorsed neither Dewey nor Roosevelt.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1944-united-states-presidential-election] At the 1944 Republican National Convention in Chicago, Dewey easily overcame Bricker and was nominated for president on the first ballot.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1944-united-states-presidential-election] Dewey, a moderate to liberal Republican, chose the conservative Bricker as his running mate.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1944-united-states-presidential-election] Dewey originally preferred fellow liberal California Governor Earl Warren, but agreed on Bricker to preserve party unity (Warren would go on to run with Dewey in the 1948 election).
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1944-united-states-presidential-election] Bricker was nominated for vice president by acclamation.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1944-united-states-presidential-election] The Republicans campaigned against the New Deal, seeking a smaller government and less-regulated economy as the end of the war seemed in sight.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1944-united-states-presidential-election] Nonetheless, Roosevelt's continuing popularity was the main theme of the campaign.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1944-united-states-presidential-election] To quiet rumors of his poor health, Roosevelt insisted on making a vigorous campaign swing in October and rode in an open car through city streets.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1944-united-states-presidential-election] Numerous campaign songs for F.D.R. were written, possibly in an effort to advertise on radio during radio's Golden Age.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1944-united-states-presidential-election] A high point of the campaign occurred when Roosevelt, speaking to a meeting of labor union leaders, gave a speech carried on national radio in which he ridiculed Republican claims that his administration was corrupt and wasteful with tax money.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1944-united-states-presidential-election] He particularly derided a Republican claim that he had sent a US Navy warship to pick up his Scottish Terrier Fala in Alaska, noting that "Fala was furious" at such rumors.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1944-united-states-presidential-election] The speech was met with loud laughter and applause from the labor leaders.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1944-united-states-presidential-election] However, American battlefield successes in Europe and the Pacific during the campaign, such as the liberation of Paris in August 1944 and the successful Battle of Leyte Gulf in the Philippines in October 1944, made President Roosevelt unbeatable.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1944-united-states-presidential-election] Throughout the campaign, Roosevelt led Dewey in all the polls by varying margins.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1944-united-states-presidential-election] On election day, the Democratic incumbent scored a fairly comfortable victory over his Republican challenger.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1944-united-states-presidential-election] Roosevelt took 36 states for 432 electoral votes (266 were needed to win), while Dewey won twelve states and 99 electoral votes.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1944-united-states-presidential-election] Dewey conceded in a radio address the following morning, but declined to personally call or to send a telegram to President Roosevelt.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1944-united-states-presidential-election] The important question had been which leader, Roosevelt or Dewey, should be chosen for the critical days of peacemaking and reconstruction following the war's conclusion.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1944-united-states-presidential-election] Most American voters concluded that they should retain the governing party, and particularly the president who represented it.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1944-united-states-presidential-election] They also felt it unsafe to do so in "wartime", in view of ever-increasing domestic disagreements.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1944-united-states-presidential-election] Dewey did better against Roosevelt than any of Roosevelt's previous three Republican opponents: Roosevelt's percentage and margin of the total vote were both less than in 1940.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1944-united-states-presidential-election] Dewey flipped the states of Wyoming, Wisconsin, and Ohio from the previous election, while Roosevelt flipped Michigan.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1944-united-states-presidential-election] Dewey also gained the personal satisfaction of finishing ahead of Roosevelt in his hometown of Hyde Park, New York, and ahead of Truman in his hometown of Independence, Missouri.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1944-united-states-presidential-election] Dewey would again become the Republican presidential nominee in 1948, challenging President Truman (who had assumed that office on FDR's death), and would again lose, though by somewhat smaller popular- and electoral-vote margins.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1944-united-states-presidential-election] Roosevelt's net vote totals in the twelve largest cities increased from 2,112,000 votes in the 1940 election to 2,230,000 votes.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1944-united-states-presidential-election] Of the 3,095 counties/independent cities making returns, Roosevelt won the most popular votes in 1,751 (56.58%) while Dewey carried 1,343 (43.39%).
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1944-united-states-presidential-election] The Texas Regular ticket carried one county (0.03%).
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1944-united-states-presidential-election] In New York, only the combined support of the American Labor and Liberal parties (pledged to Roosevelt but otherwise independent of the Democrats to maintain their identities) enabled Roosevelt to win the electoral votes of his home state.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1944-united-states-presidential-election] In 1944, the constantly growing Southern protest against Roosevelt's leadership became clearest in Texas, where 135,553 people voted against Roosevelt but not for the Republican ticket.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1944-united-states-presidential-election] The Texas Regular ticket resulted from a split in the Democratic Party in its two state conventions, May 23 and September 12, 1944.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1944-united-states-presidential-election] This ticket, which represented the Democratic element opposing the re-election of President Roosevelt, called for the "restoration of states' rights which have been destroyed by the Communist New Deal" and "restoration of the supremacy of the white race".
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1944-united-states-presidential-election] Until 1996 this was the last time in which an incumbent Democratic president won re-election after serving a full term in office.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1944-united-states-presidential-election] This was also the last election until 2012 in which the incumbent Democratic president received over 50 percent of the popular vote after receiving over 50 percent of it in the previous election.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1944-united-states-presidential-election] As of 2026, this was the most recent presidential election in which a Democratic ticket has won every state of the former Confederacy as well as the entire southern region.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1944-united-states-presidential-election] This was the first election since 1892 that a Democrat won without taking Wyoming and Ohio.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1944-united-states-presidential-election] Roosevelt is the only president to serve for more than two terms; in 1951, the Twenty-second Amendment was ratified, limiting the number of terms a person may be president.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1944-united-states-presidential-election] As he had in 1940, Roosevelt was the third of just four presidents in United States history to win re-election with a lower percentage of the electoral vote than in their prior elections; the other three are James Madison in 1812, Woodrow Wilson in 1916, and Barack Obama in 2012.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1944-united-states-presidential-election] Additionally, Roosevelt was the fourth of only five presidents to win re-election with a smaller percentage of the popular vote than in prior elections; the other four are Madison in 1812, Andrew Jackson in 1832, Grover Cleveland in 1892, and Obama in 2012.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1944-united-states-presidential-election] This is the last election in which New Hampshire and Oregon voted Democratic until 1964 and the last in which Connecticut, Delaware, Maryland, Michigan, New Jersey, New York, and Pennsylvania did so until 1960.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1994-u-s-elections] Elections were held on November 8, 1994, in the middle of Democratic President Bill Clinton's first term.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1994-u-s-elections] The elections have been described as the "Republican Revolution" because the Republican Party captured unified control of Congress for the first time since 1952.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1994-u-s-elections] Republicans picked up eight seats in the Senate and won a net of 54 seats in the House of Representatives.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1994-u-s-elections] Republicans also picked up a net of ten governorships and took control of many state legislative chambers.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1994-u-s-elections] This is the first midterm election since 1946 in which the Republicans ended unified Democratic control of Congress in a midterm election under a Democratic president.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1994-u-s-elections] Republicans were able to nationalize the election by campaigning on a "Contract with America", and the new Republican majorities passed conservative legislation such as the Telecommunications Act of 1996, the Personal Responsibility and Work Opportunity Act, and the Defense of Marriage Act.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1994-u-s-elections] The election was a major defeat for Clinton's health care plan.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1994-u-s-elections] Bush's election as Governor of Texas laid the groundwork for his successful campaign for president in 2000.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1994-u-s-elections] In the Senate elections, Republicans successfully defended all of their seats and won eight from the Democrats, defeating incumbent Senators Harris Wofford (Pennsylvania) and Jim Sasser (Tennessee), in addition to picking up six open seats in Arizona, Maine, Michigan, Ohio, Oklahoma, and Tennessee.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1994-u-s-elections] Notably, since Sasser's defeat coincided with a Republican victory in the special election to replace Al Gore, Tennessee's Senate delegation switched from entirely Democratic to entirely Republican in a single election.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1994-u-s-elections] Dole became Majority Leader, while on the Democratic side, Tom Daschle became Minority Leader after the retirement of the previous Democratic leader, George J.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1994-u-s-elections] Initially, the balance was 52–48 in favor of the Republicans, but after the power change, Democrats Richard Shelby and Ben Nighthorse Campbell switched parties, bringing the balance to 54–46.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1994-u-s-elections] The Democrats took back a seat in January 1996 in a special election in Oregon when Ron Wyden won an open seat left vacated by Republican Bob Packwood.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1994-u-s-elections] Republicans won the national popular vote for the House of Representatives by a margin of 6.8 percentage points and picked up 54 seats.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1994-u-s-elections] The South underwent a drastic transformation, as Republicans picked up 19 Southern seats, leaving them with more seats than Democrats in the South, last achieved during Reconstruction.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1994-u-s-elections] 34 incumbents, all Democrats, were defeated.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1994-u-s-elections] The incumbent Speaker, Democrat Tom Foley, lost re-election in his district, becoming the first Speaker of the House to lose re-election since Galusha Grow in 1863.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1994-u-s-elections] Other major upsets included the defeat of House Ways and Means Chairman Dan Rostenkowski and House Judiciary Chairman Jack Brooks.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1994-u-s-elections] The incumbent Republican Minority whip, Newt Gingrich, was re-elected in the Republican landslide and became Speaker as the incumbent Republican Minority Leader, Robert H.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1994-u-s-elections] The incumbent Democratic Majority Leader, Dick Gephardt, became Minority Leader.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1994-u-s-elections] Heading into the election, there were 21 seats held by Democrats, 14 held by Republicans, and one by an independent.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1994-u-s-elections] By the end of the elections, 11 seats would be held by Democrats, 24 by Republicans, and one by an independent.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1994-u-s-elections] In addition, Republicans gained the majority of state legislative seats for the first time in decades.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1994-u-s-elections] During the campaign, the United States Republican Party released a document that it called the Contract with America.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1994-u-s-elections] Many of the Contract's policy ideas originated at The Heritage Foundation, a conservative think tank.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1994-u-s-elections] The Contract with America was signed by all but two of the Republican members of the House and all of the Party's non-incumbent Republican Congressional candidates.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1994-u-s-elections] Proponents say the Contract was revolutionary in its commitment to offering specific legislation for a vote, describing in detail the precise plan of the Congressional Representatives, last achieved during the 1918 Congressional election had been run broadly on a national level.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1994-u-s-elections] Furthermore, its provisions represented the view of many conservative Republicans on the issues of shrinking the size of government, promoting lower taxes and greater entrepreneurial activity, and both tort reform and welfare reform.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1994-u-s-elections] The people voted for reform." He said that the Contract "turned out to be a brilliant political ploy.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/1994-u-s-elections] The contract tuned in to the American electorate’s deep yearning for reform in Washington, a yearning that had expressed itself in the elections of both (U.S.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/term-limits-in-the-united-states] In the politics of the United States, term limits restrict the number of terms an officeholder may serve.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/term-limits-in-the-united-states] At the federal level, the President can be elected to at most two four-year terms, per the Twenty-second Amendment to the United States Constitution which came into force on February 27, 1951.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/term-limits-in-the-united-states] Some state government offices are also term-limited, including executive, legislative, and judicial offices.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/term-limits-in-the-united-states] Analogous measures exist at the city and county level across the U.S., though many details involving local governments in that country vary depending on the location.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/term-limits-in-the-united-states] Term limits are also called **rotation in office**.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/term-limits-in-the-united-states] That terminology is often associated with Founding Father and later president Thomas Jefferson given his use of it in his political arguments.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/term-limits-in-the-united-states] Term limits date back to the American Revolution and before that, to the democracies and republics of Antiquity.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/term-limits-in-the-united-states] The Council of 500 in ancient Athens rotated its entire membership annually, as did the ephorate in ancient Sparta.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/term-limits-in-the-united-states] The Roman Republic featured a system of elected magistrates—tribunes of the plebs, aediles, quaestors, praetors, and consuls—who served a single term of one year, with re-election to the same magistracy forbidden for ten years *(see cursus honorum)*.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/term-limits-in-the-united-states] Fagan, office holding in the Roman Republic was based on "limited tenure of office" which ensured that "authority circulated frequently", helping to prevent corruption.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/term-limits-in-the-united-states] Another benefit of the *cursus honorum* or *run of offices* was to bring the "most experienced" politicians to the upper echelons of power-holding in the ancient republic.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/term-limits-in-the-united-states] Many of the founders of the United States were educated in the classics, and quite familiar with rotation in the office during antiquity.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/term-limits-in-the-united-states] The debates of that day reveal a desire to study and profit from the object lessons offered by ancient democracy.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/term-limits-in-the-united-states] Prior to independence, several colonies had already experimented with term limits.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/term-limits-in-the-united-states] Pennsylvania's plural executive was composed of twelve citizens elected for the term of three years, followed by a mandatory vacation of four years.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/term-limits-in-the-united-states] On October 2, 1789, the Continental Congress appointed a committee of thirteen to examine forms of government for the impending union of the states.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/term-limits-in-the-united-states] Unlike the Articles of Confederation, the federal constitution convention at Philadelphia omitted term limits from the U.S.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/term-limits-in-the-united-states] When the states ratified the Constitution (1787–88), several leading statesmen regarded the lack of mandatory limits to tenure as a dangerous defect, especially, they thought, as regards the presidency and the Senate.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/term-limits-in-the-united-states] Korzi says George Washington did not set the informal precedent for a two-term limit for the Presidency.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/term-limits-in-the-united-states] He only meant he was too worn out to personally continue in office.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/term-limits-in-the-united-states] It was Thomas Jefferson who made it a principle in 1808.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/term-limits-in-the-united-states] He made many statements calling for term limits in one form or another.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/term-limits-in-the-united-states] The two-term limit tradition was maintained unofficially for 132 years.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/term-limits-in-the-united-states] It was unsuccessfully challenged by Ulysses S.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/term-limits-in-the-united-states] Grant in 1880, Theodore Roosevelt in 1912, and Woodrow Wilson in 1920.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/term-limits-in-the-united-states] Roosevelt successfully ran for a third term in 1940, citing the outbreak of World War II.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/term-limits-in-the-united-states] The two Roosevelts are the only presidents to run for a third term in a general election; Grant and Wilson aimed to do so but failed to gain their parties' nominations.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/term-limits-in-the-united-states] Franklin Roosevelt was re-elected in 1944 for a fourth term amidst the United States' engagement in World War II but died shortly afterwards in office.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/term-limits-in-the-united-states] The Twenty-second Amendment to the United States Constitution was ratified in 1951, formally establishing in law the two-term limit — though it did not apply to the incumbent Harry S.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/term-limits-in-the-united-states] Truman declined to run for a third term in 1952.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/term-limits-in-the-united-states] The fact that "perpetuity in office" was not approached until the 20th century is due in part to the influence of rotation in office as a popular 19th-century concept.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/term-limits-in-the-united-states] "Ideas are, in truth, forces," and rotation in office enjoyed such normative support, especially at the local level, that it altered political reality.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/term-limits-in-the-united-states] During the American Civil War, the Confederate Constitution limited its president to one six-year term.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/term-limits-in-the-united-states] Only Jefferson Davis served as Confederate president, but he did not complete a full term in office before surrendering to the Union.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/term-limits-in-the-united-states] The practice of nomination rotation for the House of Representatives began to decline after the Civil War.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/term-limits-in-the-united-states] It took a generation or so before the direct primary system, civil service reforms, and the ethic of professionalism worked to eliminate rotation in office as a common political practice.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/term-limits-in-the-united-states] By the turn of the 20th century the era of incumbency was coming into full swing.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/term-limits-in-the-united-states] A total of eight presidents served two full terms and declined a third.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/term-limits-in-the-united-states] Three presidents served one full term and refused a second.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/term-limits-in-the-united-states] After World War II, however, an officeholder class had developed to the point that congressional tenure rivaled that of the U.S.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/term-limits-in-the-united-states] Supreme Court, where tenure is for life.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/term-limits-in-the-united-states] A movement in favor of term limits took hold in the early 1990s, and reached its apex in 1992 to 1994, a period when seventeen states enacted term limits through state legislation or state constitutional amendments.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/term-limits-in-the-united-states] Many of the laws enacted limited terms for both the state legislature and in the state's delegation to Congress.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/term-limits-in-the-united-states] As they pertain to Congress, these laws were struck down as unconstitutional by U.S.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/term-limits-in-the-united-states] Thornton* (1995), in which the court ruled, on a 5–4 vote, that state governments cannot limit the terms of members of the national government.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/term-limits-in-the-united-states] Where rotation in the legislative branch has withstood court challenges, term limits continue to garner popular support.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/term-limits-in-the-united-states] Term Limits" found that in the seventeen states where state legislators served in rotation, public support for term limits ranged from 60 to 78 percent.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/term-limits-in-the-united-states] Term limits at the federal level are restricted to the executive branch and some agencies.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/term-limits-in-the-united-states] Judicial appointments at the federal level are made for life and are not subject to election or to term limits.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/term-limits-in-the-united-states] Congress remains (since the *Thornton* decision of 1995) without electoral limits.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/term-limits-in-the-united-states] George Washington's decision in 1796 not to run for a third term has often been given credit as the start of a tradition that no president should ever run for a third term.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/term-limits-in-the-united-states] Washington wanted to retire when his first term ended in 1792, but all his advisors begged him to stand for re-election.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/term-limits-in-the-united-states] By 1796, however, he insisted on retiring, as he felt exhausted and disgusted by virulent personal attacks on his integrity.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/term-limits-in-the-united-states] His Farewell Address very briefly mentioned why he would not run for a third term and goes on to give a great deal of political advice, but it does not mention term limits.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/term-limits-in-the-united-states] After his death, his refusal to run was explained in terms of a "no-third-tradition." Crockett (2008) argues, "The argument for term limits has a solid and respectable pedigree.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/term-limits-in-the-united-states] Contrary to popular belief, however, that pedigree does not begin with George Washington." The second president, John Adams, lost re-election in 1800 to Thomas Jefferson.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/term-limits-in-the-united-states] Jefferson himself declined re-election to a third term, attributing the precedent to Washington.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/term-limits-in-the-united-states] In the 1780s, about half the states had term limits for governors.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/term-limits-in-the-united-states] The Constitutional Convention of 1787 discussed the issue and decided not to institute presidential term limits.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/term-limits-in-the-united-states] The Constitution, Washington explained, retained sufficient checks against political corruption and stagnant leadership without a presidential term limits provision.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/term-limits-in-the-united-states] Jefferson, however, strongly endorsed a policy of term limits.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/term-limits-in-the-united-states] In 1861, the Confederate States of America adopted a six-year term for their president and vice president and barred the president from seeking re-election.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/term-limits-in-the-united-states] That innovation was endorsed by many American politicians after the Civil War, most notably by Rutherford B.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/term-limits-in-the-united-states] Grant was urged to run for a third term in 1876, but he refused.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/term-limits-in-the-united-states] He did try to win the 1880 nomination but was defeated in part because of popular anti-third-term sentiment.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/term-limits-in-the-united-states] Theodore Roosevelt had already served over seven years and in 1912, after a four-year hiatus, ran for a third term.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/term-limits-in-the-united-states] He was criticized for doing so, and attempted assassin John Schrank stated that his motivation for shooting Roosevelt was preventing a third term.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/term-limits-in-the-united-states] The 1912 election was ultimately won by Woodrow Wilson.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/term-limits-in-the-united-states] Roosevelt (president, 1933–1945) was the only president to be elected more than twice; he won a third term in 1940 and a fourth term in 1944 (though he died in office three months into his fourth term).
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/term-limits-in-the-united-states] This gave rise to a successful move to formalize the traditional two-term limit by amending the U.S.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/term-limits-in-the-united-states] As ratified in 1951, the Twenty-Second Amendment says, "no person shall be elected to the office of President more than twice." The new amendment explicitly did not apply to the incumbent president, Harry S.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/term-limits-in-the-united-states] However, Truman declined to seek re-election to a third term in 1952.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/term-limits-in-the-united-states] Reformers during the early 1990s used the initiative and referendum to put congressional term limits on the ballot in 24 states.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/term-limits-in-the-united-states] Voters in eight of these states approved the congressional term limits by an average electoral margin of two to one.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/term-limits-in-the-united-states] It was an open question whether states had the constitutional authority to enact these limits.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/term-limits-in-the-united-states] 779 (1995), that states cannot impose term limits upon their federal representatives or senators.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/term-limits-in-the-united-states] In the 1994 U.S. elections, part of the "Contract With America" Republican platform included legislation for term limits in Congress.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/term-limits-in-the-united-states] After winning the majority, a Republican congressman brought a constitutional amendment to the House floor that proposed limiting members of the Senate to two six-year terms and members of the House to six two-year terms.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/term-limits-in-the-united-states] However, this rate of rotation was so slow (the life-tenured Supreme Court averages about 16 years) that the congressional version of term limits garnered little support among the populist backers of term limits, including U.S.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/term-limits-in-the-united-states] Term Limits, the largest private organization pushing for congressional term limits.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/term-limits-in-the-united-states] The bill got only a bare majority (227–204), falling short of the two-thirds majority (290) needed for constitutional amendments.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/term-limits-in-the-united-states] Three other term limit amendment bills failed to get more than 200 votes.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/term-limits-in-the-united-states] Defeated in Congress and overridden by the Supreme Court, the federal term limit movement was brought to a halt.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/term-limits-in-the-united-states] The term limits intended simultaneously to reform state legislatures (as distinguished from the federal congressional delegations) remain in force, however, in fifteen states.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/term-limits-in-the-united-states] Sabato revived the debate over term limits by arguing in *A More Perfect Constitution* that the success and popularity of term limits at the state level suggests that they should be adopted at the federal level as well.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/term-limits-in-the-united-states] He specifically put forth the idea of congressional term limits and suggested a national constitutional convention be used to accomplish the amendment, since the Congress would be unlikely to propose and adopt any amendment that limits its own power.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/term-limits-in-the-united-states] Some state legislators have also expressed their opinions on term limits.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/term-limits-in-the-united-states] Hawaii Senate in 1990 (designated as Memorial 400 in the U.S.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/term-limits-in-the-united-states] House of Representatives) approved Hawaii Senate Resolution No.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/term-limits-in-the-united-states] 41—unicameral only (see *Congressional Record* of September 28, 1998, at page 22655).
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/term-limits-in-the-united-states] It took eight years for this resolution to find its way into the *Congressional Record* and to be correctly referred to the Committee on the Judiciary—and even then, its text was not provided in the *Congressional Record.* Back in 1990, Hawaii's S.R.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/term-limits-in-the-united-states] House of Representatives, and was designated as Memorial 416, (*Congressional Record* of June 6, 1990, at pages 13,262 and 13,263) but the resolution was erroneously referred to the Committee on Energy and Commerce.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/term-limits-in-the-united-states] Utah Legislature in 1990 (designated as POM-644 in the U.S.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/term-limits-in-the-united-states] Senate) approved Utah Senate Joint Resolution No.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/term-limits-in-the-united-states] 24 (see *Congressional Record* of September 27, 1994, at page 26033, with verbatim text provided).
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/term-limits-in-the-united-states] It took four years for this resolution to find its way into the U.S.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/term-limits-in-the-united-states] Idaho Legislature in 1992 (designated as Memorial 401 in the U.S.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/term-limits-in-the-united-states] House of Representatives) approved Idaho Senate Joint Memorial No.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/term-limits-in-the-united-states] 116 (see *Congressional Record* of April 29, 1992, at page 9804—text not provided in the *Congressional Record*).
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/term-limits-in-the-united-states] Florida Legislature in 2012 (designated as POM-122 in the U.S.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/term-limits-in-the-united-states] Senate) approved Florida House Memorial No.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/term-limits-in-the-united-states] 83 (see *Congressional Record* of July 25, 2012, at page S5378, with verbatim text provided).
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/term-limits-in-the-united-states] On February 10, 2016, Florida lawmakers approved House Memorial No.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/term-limits-in-the-united-states] 417 calling upon Congress, pursuant to Article V of the Federal Constitution, to assemble a Convention to prepare a constitutional amendment that would establish term limits upon members of Congress.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/term-limits-in-the-united-states] Legal scholars have discussed whether or not to impose term limits on the Supreme Court of the United States.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/term-limits-in-the-united-states] Currently, Supreme Court justices are appointed for life "during good behavior." A sentiment has developed, among certain scholars, that the Supreme Court may not be accountable in a way that is most in line with the spirit of checks and balances.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/term-limits-in-the-united-states] Equally, scholars have argued that life tenure has taken on a new meaning in a modern context.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/term-limits-in-the-united-states] Changes in medical care have markedly raised life expectancy and therefore have allowed justices to serve for longer than ever before.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/term-limits-in-the-united-states] Many of the proposals center around a term limit for justices that would be 10, 18 years to 25 years in length.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/term-limits-in-the-united-states] Calabresi, Lindgren, and Carrington have also proposed that when justices have served out their proposed 18-year term they should be able to sit on other Federal Courts until retirement, death, or removal.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/term-limits-in-the-united-states] Fairleigh Dickinson University's PublicMind Poll measured American voters' attitudes towards various proposed Supreme Court reforms, including implementing term limits.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/term-limits-in-the-united-states] The 2010 poll found that a majority of Americans were largely unaware of a proposal to impose a term limit of 18 years, as 82% reported they had heard little or nothing at all.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/term-limits-in-the-united-states] Notwithstanding a lack of awareness, 52% of Americans approved of limiting terms to 18 years, while 35% disapproved.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/term-limits-in-the-united-states] When asked how old is too old for a Supreme Court judge to serve if he seems healthy, 48% said "no limit as long as he is healthy", while 31% agreed that anyone over the age of 70 is too old.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/term-limits-in-the-united-states] Some state lawmakers have officially expressed to Congress a desire for a federal constitutional amendment to limit terms of Supreme Court justices as well as of judges of federal courts below the Supreme Court level.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/term-limits-in-the-united-states] In 1978, the Tennessee General Assembly adopted House Joint Resolution No.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/term-limits-in-the-united-states] 21 on the subject (designated as POM-612 by the U.S.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/term-limits-in-the-united-states] Senate and quoted in full in the *Congressional Record* of April 25, 1978, at page 11437).
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/term-limits-in-the-united-states] In 1998, the Louisiana House of Representatives adopted House Resolution No.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/term-limits-in-the-united-states] 120 on the subject (designated as POM-511 by the U.S.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/term-limits-in-the-united-states] Senate and quoted in full in the *Congressional Record* of July 17, 1998, at page 16076).
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/term-limits-in-the-united-states] Term limits for state officials have existed since colonial times.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/term-limits-in-the-united-states] The Pennsylvania Charter of Liberties of 1682, and the colonial frame of government of the same year, both authored by William Penn, provided for triennial rotation of the provincial council—the upper house of the colonial legislature.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/term-limits-in-the-united-states] The Delaware Constitution of 1776 limited the governor to a single three-year term; currently, the governor of Delaware can serve two four-year terms.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/term-limits-in-the-united-states] Governors of 37 states and 4 territories are subject to various term limits, while the governors of 13 states, Puerto Rico, and the mayor of Washington, D.C., may serve an unlimited number of terms.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/term-limits-in-the-united-states] Each state's gubernatorial term limits are prescribed by its state constitution, with the exception of Wyoming, whose limits are found in its statutes.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/term-limits-in-the-united-states] Territorial term limits are prescribed by its constitution in the Northern Mariana Islands, the Organic Acts in Guam and the U.S.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/term-limits-in-the-united-states] Virgin Islands, and by statute in American Samoa.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/term-limits-in-the-united-states] Uniquely, Virginia prohibits its governors from serving consecutive terms, although former governors are eligible to serve again as governor after a specified period (currently, 4 years) out of office.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/term-limits-in-the-united-states] Several other states formerly had this "no succession" rule (which was part of Virginia's original constitution in 1776), but all have eliminated the prohibition except Virginia by 2000 (including Mississippi, which repealed it in 1986, and Kentucky, which repealed it in 1992).
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/term-limits-in-the-united-states] Equivalently, the governors of Indiana and Oregon are limited to serving 8 out of any 12 years.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/term-limits-in-the-united-states] Conversely, the governors of Montana and Wyoming are limited to two terms, serving 8 out of any 16 years.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/term-limits-in-the-united-states] Finally, the governors of the following states and territory are limited to two terms during their respective lifetime: Arkansas, California, Delaware, Michigan, Mississippi, Missouri, Nevada, North Dakota, the Northern Mariana Islands, and Oklahoma.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/term-limits-in-the-united-states] Former governor of California Jerry Brown, however, served four non-consecutive terms because his first two terms were before limits were passed in California, and the limits did not apply to individuals' prior terms.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/term-limits-in-the-united-states] The governors of New Hampshire and Vermont may serve unlimited two-year terms.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/term-limits-in-the-united-states] The governors (or equivalent) in the following states, district, and territory may serve unlimited four-year terms: Connecticut, Idaho, Illinois, Iowa, Massachusetts, Minnesota, New York, Texas, Utah, Washington, Wisconsin, District of Columbia, and Puerto Rico.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/term-limits-in-the-united-states] The governor of Utah was previously limited to serving three terms, but all term limit laws have since been repealed by the legislature.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/term-limits-in-the-united-states] In 2022, voters in North Dakota approved a constitutional amendment that limits the governor to no more than two four-year terms.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/term-limits-in-the-united-states] The amendment only applies to individuals elected after 2023.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/term-limits-in-the-united-states] Seventeen state legislatures currently have term limits.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/term-limits-in-the-united-states] The earliest state legislative term limit was enacted in 1990, and the most recent was enacted in 2022.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/term-limits-in-the-united-states] Term limits only went into effect years after they were enacted.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/term-limits-in-the-united-states] Legislative term limits have been repealed or overturned in six states.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/term-limits-in-the-united-states] Term limits for state legislatures were adopted by Idaho and Utah in 1994, but repealed by their legislatures in 2002 and 2003 respectively.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/term-limits-in-the-united-states] Some localities impose term limits for local office.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/term-limits-in-the-united-states] A two-term limit was imposed on New York City Council members and citywide elected officials (except for district attorneys) in New York City after a 1993 referendum (see the Charter of the City of New York, § 1138).
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/term-limits-in-the-united-states] On November 3, 2008, however, when Michael Bloomberg was in his second term of mayor, the City Council approved the extension of the two-term limit to a three-term limit; one year later, he was elected to a third term.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/term-limits-in-the-united-states] The two-term limit was reinstated after a referendum in 2010.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/term-limits-in-the-united-states] Research studies have shown that legislative term limits increase legislative polarization, reduce the legislative skills of politicians, reduce the legislative productivity of politicians, weaken legislatures vis-à-vis the executive, and reduce voter turnout.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/term-limits-in-the-united-states] Parties respond to the implementation of term limits by recruiting candidates for office on more partisan lines.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/term-limits-in-the-united-states] States that implement term limits in the state legislatures are associated with also developing more powerful House speakers.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/term-limits-in-the-united-states] Term limits have not proven to reduce campaign spending, reduce the gender gap in political representation, increase the diversity of law-makers, or increase the constituent service activities of law-makers.
[src:term-limits-in-the-united-states/term-limits-in-the-united-states] Term limits have been linked to lower growth in revenues and expenditures.
